SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient came in for a Moderna Vaccine. He had no DUR's. I gave him the vaccine at 9:25am. He waited the 15min. He walked over to the blood pressure machine and took his blood pressure. He then said He was starting to feel funny. Pharmacist took his blood pressure. Initially it was156/94 pulse 114. She gave him a water. She checked on him again a few minutes later and it was 166/76 pulse 103. I check on him. He said he felt tingly and his throat was still scratchy. But he was not having any problem breathing. He said he thought he was having a panic attack. I recommended Benadryl. I gave him 50mg Benadryl orally at 10:15. He was still feeling funny after and we called a manager to get paramedics ( he wanted paramedics called). He was a little shaky and still felt bad. Paramedics arrived a little after 10:30. They ran some tests and also said they thought it was a panic attack. They did not administer any meds to him that I saw, but did take his BG, BP, and check his heart. They went ahead and wheeled him to the ER. Patient apologized, I think he felt embarrassed.
LAB_DATA: Blood Pressure: 156/94 Pulse 114, Blood Pressure 166/76 Pulse 103.

On Monday 4/19/21 upon waking noticed hearing problem: 1) Hissing in both ears, 2) Inability to equalize inner ear pressure [Same problem that one experiences in airplanes at high altitudes], 3) Pressure in inner ear [Similar as having water in your ear], and 4) difficulty in hearing conversations on the telephone.  On Monday 4/19/21, PCP prescribed Allegra.  On Tuesday 4/20/21, I requested PCP give me a prescription for an antibiotic because I do not have and have never had a history of allergy problems, but have had a history of sinus problems.  Began taking amoxicillin on Tuesday 4/20/21.  Today is Thursday 4/22/21, and I have seen no change in my hearing problem. SYMPTOM_TEXT: -Mild tingling along left trigeminal nerve and left arm within 30 minutes. BP was checked around 20 minutes after injection. It was 168/106 with heart rate of 90.  My usual BP is 120/68 with 62 heartrate. My BP has never been that high before as far as I know. Within another 30 minutes it was down to 145/94 and heart rate of 82,  and I  was released from observation to go home. I was seated and calm throughout episode. I felt "off" for several hours afterward, but had no way to check my BP.  My heartrate averaged around 75-85 during that time.  -Fatigue followed feeling "off" for another 30 hours.

Patient reported that three previous times after receiving season flu vaccine, she developed accelerated heartrate and shortness of breath, but that it had been four years since that last happened. We instructed to remain her for 30 minutes after the shot rather than 15. About 10 minutes after receiving the COVID injection, she developed increased hearth rate and shortness of breath. She reported she also felt nauseous. We removed her face mask and had her lie on her side on the floor. We called 911 and remained with her until the ambulance left. She looked less pale and was feeling somewhat better by the time the ambulance arrived, but   Patient returned later in the morning, looking and feeling fine. She told us that the ER assessment was that it was not an allergic reaction to the vaccine, but rather something in the vaccine that triggers her increased heartrate. She told us that when this happens, it compounds her anxiety, and she attributes what happened to being as much a panic attack as a physical reaction. She also told us that due to her agoraphobia, she feels anxious in unfamiliar surroundings. She had never been to our pharmacy before.
LAB_DATA: ER visit - Not known what tests were done - Patient returned to pharmacy to report to us that everything was fine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient reports symptoms of right hand numbness and weakness and slurred speech.  These occurred around 7:30 pm but it is unclear exactly what day they happened as one physician noted the day of the vaccine and another noted 2 days after the vaccine.  The slurred speech resolved in 5 minutes but the hand continued to have some numbness and tingling.  Patient was referred to the neurologist who diagnosed a TIA and ordered further workup.  Patient was found to have calcified plaques in the left proximal internal carotid artery with severe stenosis.  She was referred to vascular surgery for an endarterectomy.  During the process of clearing her for surgery she was seen by a cardiologist who requested that this event be reported to VAERS.

Immediately after the shot, I started to feel my pulse race slightly. After half an hour this progressed to a flushing heat in my neck and ears. This was an anticipated histamine type reaction to the vaccine that I have gotten to a number of triggers this year. The second day after the shot, I developed a 1-2 degree fever, which stayed with me for the past week, and still has not resolved. My pulse has stopped racing after about the third day, however, and I don't feel so dizzy. I have taken extra strength Tylenol to control the fever and reactions for the first 4 days around the clock to avoid my pulse spiking, and the last 2 days I took one dose of Tylenol each day when the fever rose again.

Ii got he vaccinator on 3/5 and went home.  the first night around 9p, I started to feel chills, Had a really big temporal headache.  I thought it was a reaction to vaccination, I took Tylenol PM, layer down and woke up in the middle of the night, in a full body sweat.  I went strait into chills, changed my clothes.  Layed back own and awoke the next morning, with chills and temp of 101.  I had body ache but proceeded with my day.  I continued to have chills, I went out to my elderly parents, took them food and had dinner.  Upon arrival home, had high fever 103...no Tylenol.  Awoke still w/ chills and high fever and this was Sunday.  Stayed in Sunday then the afternoon, felt like I needed to seek help.  I went to get a rapid test at Medical Center and it came back Neg.  Went back home, I could now sense that my taste was altered.  I then continued to have a high fever but they would only come at night.  Body sweat, aches, chills cont'd on Sunday.  Monday still had same s/s and Tuesday, I thought that I should seek more medical attention.  I went to an Urgent Care 3/9/21.  They then did a nose swab and felt that it would come back Neg.  I went home and on Thursday 3/11/2021 I got a call that I was positive.  Did isolate.  But from 3/5 to 3/11 then I lost taste/smell.  Came out of isolation 3/20 and on 3/21 my whole left side of fact, shoulder and leg went numb for approx 1hr.  Then my wife said that I was talking a little slow in my response.  Next morning my left shoulder was hurting and I had pain.  The Urgent care provider wanted to r/o TIA  so he sent me to ER for full work up and that doctor said he saw nothing.  He didi say that it could be Covid related and/or possible TIA.  "I am feeling good today"  There is no residual but because of the left shoulder pain I did go back to Urgent Care.  Got cortisone inject and MRI.  My PCP then told me that I had a partial "tear" in my left shoulder but I do exercise every day and could have done it then.
LAB_DATA: See Urgent Care, and ER Visit Reports

Patient (DOB 6/11/1980) received dose 1 of the Pfizer COVID vaccine (lot EW0162, expiration 7/2021) at 1050. At 1052, patient laid down on the ground with her feet propped up on her chair in the observation area. PHN and RN approached the patient to assess. Patient reported blurry vision and feeling as though she was going to faint before she laid down. Patient reported a fear of needles and fainting with previous injections. Vital signs: O2 98%, pulse 72, blood pressure 120/90, respirations 14. Patient reported eating breakfast then going on a run before coming to the vaccine POD. Patient denied allergies, medications, or medical conditions. At 1058, patient reported symptoms were improving. Vital signs: O2 97%, pulse 70, blood pressure 120/95, respirations 14. At 1102, the patient sat up, drank some water, stated she felt wobbly and laid back down. Vital signs at 1104: O2 98%, pulse 66, blood pressure 120/90, respirations 14. Patient sat up reporting decreased dizziness. At 1114, vital signs: respirations 16, O2 99%, pulse 72, blood pressure 120/98. At 1116, patient stood up momentarily while monitored closely by PHN  and RN, then laid down again reporting feeling dizzy. Vital signs at 1118, O2 96%, pulse 69, respirations 16, blood pressure 120/90. Patient sat up, then laid down again reporting dizziness. SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 4/14/21 I started having chest pain and pressure.  I was seen in Urgent Care that day and an EKG, Chest xray, and lab work was preformed. I proceeded to have left sided weakness,  difficulty speaking, slurred speech, and loss of motor skills.  I was taken to the ER.  They did a CT scan, blood work, and an ekg.  All were normal.  I was admitted to the hospital and they did MRI or the head, MRA of the neck, MRI of the neck and spine, Echocardiogram, Stress test, and further blood work.  Everything came back normal.  I saw Neurology inpatient and was discharged to follow up outpatient.  I still have coordination  difficulty and I do not have all of my motor skills back yet.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: received the second dose of the Moderna Covid vaccine and was in the waiting area when she advised us that she was feeling lightheaded. We gave her a bottled water and moved her into the counseling area for observation. Approximately 5 minutes later passed out while seated in the chair. We immediately called 911 and rushed to ascertain her level of distress. It was determined that she was still breathing but she was unresponsive. While attempting to bring her to she began to vomit a small amount of material at which time I moved her forward to prevent aspiration. Shortly thereafter regained consciousness. Her breathing returned to normal and we advised her that she had passed out momentarily and she should relax and breathe slowly while waiting on the paramedics to arrive. I used a store monitor to get her blood pressure (159/97) and pulse (79). I asked if she had diabetes or blood sugar issues and she responded no. The paramedics arrived shortly thereafter and again took her vitals. Everything was within normal range but they advised her she should ride with them to the hospital for monitoring. refused and was escorted by the paramedics to her car. Later in the evening I called to make sure everything was still ok. She responded that after she got home she rested and had a small meal and ever since she has been perfectly fine.

I did not seek medical attention the second time as the burning sensation disappeared quickly and I was able to lower my heart rate through breathing exercises. I left the medical location about 15-20 minutes after the episode and drove home without incident.  I had moderate arm pain and  fatigue the rest of the day. On the morning of 4/22/2021, I woke up feeling well except arm pain. At around 7:45  that morning, I had a sudden shaky episode where my watch registered heartrates from 105 up through 153. My hands tingled and  they developed  a significant tremor. These symptoms are typical for me during a panic attack. I took 1/2 of a Clonazepam and did some breathing exercise and was able to get my heart rate back to normal (in the 70s) within 10 or 15 minutes.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Around 1am Tuesday, April 6th (the day after the vaccination), developed acute onset fever (Tm 102), chills, extreme muscle aches, profound malaise/fatigue, nausea/vomiting, and diarrhea.  Those symptoms lasted about 24 hours and, by midday Wednesday, she was back to her baseline of intermittent dry cough, shortness of breath, and no smell or taste.  It wasn't until Sunday, two days ago, that she developed sharp, pinpoint right superior parietal scalp pain that, after a few doses of OTC Aleve, did somewhat improve.  Other than two 220 mg OTC Aleve tabs twice daily, she has not been taking anything else for her symptoms other than prescribed asthma/allergy meds. She states that her shortness of breath has been helped from the use of albuterol as needed.  Unfortunately, the Aleve has not helped with her chest pain, which she describes as a "constant ache."  Initially, patient had some pleurisy, but that has apparently cleared up.     No history of CVT, PE, and she does not smoke or take oral contraceptives.
LAB_DATA: At her convenient care visit on April 13th, other than a CRP being elevated to 0.30 mg/dL (barely above the 0.29 mg/dL threshold for the upper limits of normal), the rest of her labs were unremarkable.  They included the following: EKG, CBC, CMP, Lipase, Troponin, D-dimer, ESR, Procalcitonin, COVID-19 (rapid), chest x-ray, and TSH.    Her urine dip was abnormal for trace leukocyte esterase, trace protein, small ketone, 1+ bilirubin, and trace blood.  That being said, her urine culture was negative.  Of note, pregnancy test was negative.
OTHER_MEDS: Fluticasone, montelukast, sertraline, albuterol, budesonide-formoterol, tiotropium bromide, acetaminophen, naproxen

Because I have endometrosis, I take my birth control continuously to suppress menstruation and have not had a period for years. By day 3 (Saturday) I had a full, heavy period and horrible menstrual cramps and spent the entire day in bed under a heating blanket. My period lasted that whole week until the following Monday. I discussed this with my gynecologist and he said he has never heard of anyone having this happen from the vaccine and just assumed it was extremely coincidental.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was contacted on 4/18 at 730p by one of our volunteer vaccinators regarding the vaccination event on 4/17. At that event, she vaccinated an individual and expressed concern that the needle had not retracted and was lodged in the deltoid muscle. Upon further investigation, it had fully retracted as intended and no further workup was necessary. However, during our conversation on 4/18, she expressed concern that she had not known how to retract the needle during her first vaccination and had capped the needle. After thinking about this situation on 4/18, she was concerned that she believes she used the same needle to vaccinate the 2nd individual (i.e. the person who there was initial concern about a needle being lodged in the deltoid). Dr. (Name) is not aware of the name of either individual. Given these concerns, we will need to identify the individual, contact them, undergo the protocol for needlstick injury, and also vaccinate them if they are open to another vaccination. The plan is to review the encounter forms to find the two individuals and compare them against the scheduled appointments. Once identified, we will ask the source patient to undergo lab draws (either at HD or their urgent care) as well as ask the injured patient to undergo baseline labs.  ** Update**  Patient scheduled for vaccination on 4/26 Source patient negative for HIV, HepC Ab. HBsAg pending

That night I had fatigue and fever. My temp went up to 102.7. I alternated Tylenol and Motrin every two hours during the night and my fever finally broke the next morning. I had about 12 hours total of fever. I also had a headache and brain fog.  For about two days after, I still had the brain fog along with chilling and sweating and a headache. Four days after my dose, on 24th, I noticed that my left side of my neck was swollen as well as my axilla - and it was swollen all the way up to my jaw line. It was diffuse swelling but in the middle of that I had a hard knot on the middle clavicle. I called my doctor (January). I saw her seven or eight days after vaccine. At the time, there wasn't really any reports of swollen lymph nodes yet. Dr. felt like it was lymph nodes inflamed from vaccine. She decided to wait four weeks and re-check. (March 2 was follow-up.) The diffuse swelling is gone and the tenderness is gone now - but the hard knot is still there on middle of clavicle. They did an ultrasound - 9 mm sub clavicular knot - lymph node. An enlarged lymph node.   I went back four weeks after that visit for the my annual exam  (April 12) and they lymph node is still there - enlarged sitting on top of my clavicle. It is hard. It's non tender at this time. Dr. told me it could be there for a long time.
LAB_DATA: Ultrasound - March 17- that was done - enlarged lymph node -9 mm subclavicular  bloodwork -at the doctor office April 12th - everything was normal

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 2/18/21, 10 days after receiving the vaccine, I donated blood as usual.  About 30 minutes later I was light headed, had abdominal cramping pain, bowel emptying and possibly fainted.  I was transported by EMTs to the ER and was later diagnosed with inflamitory bowel by a CT scan.  I took antibiotics and was feeling fine.  My gastroenterologist performed a colonoscopy on 3/24/21 and the findings were that I was healed and tissue samples were normal.  3/25/21 I had an annual physical and was told I was in good health.  Later that afternoon I began feeling light headed upon standing.  In the night I called my health insurance hotline because my blood oxygen meter was beeping  continuously.  The Dr. on call told me to go by ambulance to the ER.  When sitting or lying down, I felt fine and all the tests at the ER for my heart and my vital signs were good.  A few hours later, they did a hest Xray and then a CT scan of my lungs which showed a saddle embulism. Two days after the vaccine, on 4/12/2021, I woke up with itchy red rashes all over both of my legs & feet (~30 small-med size). Took 2 doses of Zyrtec & Benadryl 50mg twice that day so it wouldn?t itch so much. Also applied mometasone ointment to rashes.   On 4/13/2021, I did a video visit with a doctor.  She said my rashes were probably due to an immune response to the J&J covid vaccine (meaning it is working) & it didn?t look serious since it was only on my legs.  She said to continue the Zyrtec up to 2x/day, Benadryl every 6 hrs if needed, & apply mometasone steroid ointment for the rashes 1x/day.  On 4/14/2021, the rashes have improved and I had less than 10 rashes on my legs.  Since I still had some rashes, I continued to take 1 Zyrtec 10mg in the morning & applied mometasone ointment to the rashes.   On 4/16/2021, the rashes had resolved.
OTHER_MEDS: Pristiq, Zyrtec, vitamin D, Nutrafol hair supplements, vitamin C
PRIOR_VAX: Tetanus vaccine- had shaking chills/felt cold afterwards (~10 yrs ago)

In addition to that, my eyes were bloodshot and had drainage coming from them and in the morning, it appeared that they had like a lining of film over them. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt has received second dose of the Moderna series. He had completed his fifteen  minutes of observation and after standing to leave, he collapsed onto the floor hitting his head at 1152. Myself,RN rushed over and began to evaluate condition.  Pt was oriented x4 and stated he had become light headed after standing. Stated that his head hurt from hitting it on the floor. Began monitoring vital signs. Initial VS showed BP of 138/82, Pulse of 83, and respirations at 14. Applied oxygen per nasal cannula until we could monitor oxygen level which was found to be 96%. After continuing to  talk with pt, he again passed out while still laying down. We were able to awaken him and he was still oriented x4. . Second VS  at 1159 showed BP of 130/82, P 82, and 02 of 96.  Pt reported his history of seizures. Continued to monitor. Third set of VS at 1204 were BP 124/78, P 78, R 12, 02 96. Police arrived at 1205 and ambulance arrived at 1209. Pt refused to be taken in  by ambulance and continued to converse. We sat pt up to sitting position. At 1207, BP was 124/80, P 79, and 02 96. He was then moved up to sit in chair but after sitting there at approximately 1215, pt again passed out but was supported by the EMT.  After regaining consciousness, he then agreed to be transported to hospital via ambulance.

Patient reported on form that they had a previous allergic reaction to a meningitis vaccine in the past (10+ years ago). Immunizer informed patient to stay at pharmacy for the next 30 minutes following the vaccination to be able to monitor for allergic reaction. At around minutes 20-30, we checked in on patient who said she was experiencing shortness of breath. She began administering her inhaler that she had on hand (Ventolin/albuterol), it was not having any noticeable effect. Patient reported worsening shortness of breath and reported that she felt a swelling sensation and felt that her ears were swelling. She was visibly struggling with breathing. At this time we helped her back into the immunization area for privacy. Myself (pharmacist) and the other pharmacist on duty were talking her through breathing and trying to calm her down while helping her contact a family member in the area. We administered 1 dose of epinephrine 0.3 mg after about 10-15 minutes of her experiencing a visible serious allergic reaction. Right before administering the Epinephrine we instructed a technician on staff to call EMS. Within about 5 minutes of administering epi the patient began to be able to breathe better. We kept trying to keep her calm and within 10 minutes from administering EPI the EMS had arrived and they took her outside to allow her more fresh air to determine if she needed to go to the hospital.
OTHER_MEDS: Patient had a prescription for Ventolin albuterol inhaler
PRIOR_VAX: meningitis vaccine over 10 years ago based on patient report

Patient was initially seen on 4/16 in the ED and discharged after complaints of myalgias.  She was tested for COVID and discharged home and instructed to take acetaminophen.  On 4/20, she returned to the ED with continued complaints including abdominal pain, nausea, and diarrhea.  She also complained of dizziness when she stands, and that her skin and eyes were jaundiced.  The patient was hypotensive and was not responding to IV fluids.  She was started on vasopressors.  She was found to be in acute liver and kidney failure.  She was emergently intubated and ended up being transferred to hospital.  Due to the nature of her condition, the above therapies were continued and CRRT was started due to acidosis.  A bicarb drip was started and was continuous.  Arrangements were made to transfer the patient to hospital once stable enough.  It was thought that she was in HLH.  She was also empirically started on hydrocortisone, later changed to dexamethasone.  She was started on antibiotics - cefepime, Flagyl, and vancomycin. She has now been transferred to hospital.  Outcome unknown at this time.  4/22

Primary care called back around 3:35pm. she discussed steroid and meds or ER. I suggested both, go to ER to see what outcome is and then steroid possibly. Numbness and pressure continued while at work. I took two baby aspirin when I got off work. Saturday morning, I went to ER. Ct Scan with and without contrast done on head and neck. Doppler was done and no clotting was detected at that time. I was told by Dr. to see my Primary care physician or come back to see ER if symptoms worsened. I contacted my primary care on Monday and left message. They called back and made appointment to see me in office for Tuesday. Dr. suggested to use steroid and I asked to do therapy. Wednesday night excessive pressure, numbness, tightness in jaw and front of neck. Contacted primary care Dr. and called Clinic to learn for Stroke Neurology. Thursday, saw fire stars twice throughout the day. Called Poison control and put in report. This is second VAERS report that I have made.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 5 minutes after vaccine administered, patient started feeling nauseous and dizzy. She was also pale and clammy.  Offered patient water and allowed to remove face mask. Instructed on breathing slowly in through the nose and out through the mouth. This helped briefly but then patient verbalized that she was feeling more light headed and thought she should lie down on exam table. Remained at patient's side but did not allow her to stand up in order to relocate from chair to exam table. Approximately 7 minutes after vaccine administration, patient briefly lost consciousness for less than 30 seconds and had slight jerking movements during this time. Remained at patient's side and prevented her from falling out of chair, hitting head, or other injury during syncopal event. After patient regained consciousness, she began sipping on water. A cold, wet paper towel was placed to the back of her neck. Continued to observe patient in exam room for another 5 minutes then she was escorted to waiting area by provider. Waiting area was just outside exam room and patient remained in the presence of a patient care technician, as well as her mother. Patient remained in waiting area for a total observation time of 30 minutes. No other adverse events occurred. Patient and mother both reported that patient does not do well after vaccines and has had similar symptoms after other vaccines in the past.
PRIOR_VAX: Unsure of vaccine, date, or other pertinent info

This non-serious solicited report (USASL2021053617) was reported on 07/APR/2021 by a consumer from a commercial program (PSP00046b) and involves a 61 year old male patient who had headache [PT: headache], nausea [PT: nausea], tongue swelling [PT: swollen tongue], could not process his breath [PT: dyspnoea] and could not swallow his saliva [PT: dysphagia] while receiving Enbrel with Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector. No historical medical condition was reported. The patient's current medical condition included psoriatic arthritis. The patient's concomitant medications included methotrexate. The patient's co-suspect medication included covid-19 vaccine. The patient began Enbrel with Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector on an unknown date. It was reported that the patient was using Enbrel for about five to six years. On an unknown date in MAR/2021, the patient received a recent injection of Enbrel. On 27/MAR/2021 at 10:00 AM, the patient received covid-19 vaccine. On the same day, the patient had nausea and headache but then it went away. On the same day at 05:30 PM, the patient had tongue swelling. The patient could not swallow his saliva and could not process his breath. Subsequently, the patient went to ER (Emergency room) and was started on Benadryl (diphenhydramine hydrochloride), prednisone and ranitidine. The patient was instructed by the physician not to receive a second dose of covid vaccine. The outcome of the events headache and nausea was reported as recovered/resolved. The outcome of the events swollen tongue, dyspnoea and dysphagia was reported as unknown. The events headache, nausea were resolved on 27/MAR/2021. Action taken with Enbrel with Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector was reported as unknown for the events headache, nausea, swollen tongue, dyspnoea and dysphagia. The causal relationship between the events headache, nausea, swollen tongue, dyspnoea, dysphagia and Enbrel with Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector was not provided by the consumer. Follow up has been requested for lot number.  Causality Assessment: Events Swallowing difficult, Breathing difficult, Swelling of tongue and Nausea were assessed to be not related to etanercept.; Sender's Comments: Based on a temporal association and the known safety profile, the reported events are considered possibly related to BNT162B2. The events were unrelated to etanercept.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

I awoke at approximately 02:00 of the morning following the second dose, in a cold sweat and shivering so hard that I could not move (locked in a fetal position). This lasted about 30 minutes, after which I fell back asleep, exhausted. The next time that I woke up, I was walking into wall between the bedroom and the bathroom (I have no history of sleepwalking). For much of the remainder of the night I experienced multiple episodes of somnambulance, each time awakening when I ran into some object (bathroom counter, television, bookcase). The last time that I woke up, at approximately 07:00, I must have been standing and simply fell over; my head bouncing off the ground is what caused me to wake up. For the entirety of the day after vaccination (04/12/21) I felt as if I had the flu: chills (though no/very mild fever < 99 F) accompanied by shivering, sometimes convulsive; sore muscles; hyperalgesia (light touch perceived as painful); lethargic; strong sense of malaise; loss of appetite. As stated, this lasted for the entire day, through the time that I went to sleep for the night (2300). The next day, 04/13/21 I felt completely back to normal with the exception that some muscles were slightly sore, possibly due to the exercise of an entire day spent shivering.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Saturday, April 3rd I got my first Pfizer Covid shot. I didn?t have any side effects like what they said could happen such as Covid symptoms.  On Tuesday, April 13th, 10 days after I had gotten the shot I noticed these red marks by my eye, it was in the morning and they came out suddenly so I thought I had gotten bit by some thing.   Over those previous 10 days I noticed that my hands were extremely sore but I have arthritis in my fingers and can have tightening and soreness when the weathers bad so I chalked it up to that.  Even though it was worse than what it normally would be.  By Friday the 16th, the reddened areas of my face were swollen, my lymph nodes in my neck and around my ear started to swell.  My cheek bone,in jaw bone, and eye socket were in terrible pain.  I went to medical and they thought it was a spider bite that was getting infected they put me on an anabiotic.  I have pictures.  Saturday the 17th I was so exhausted!  I could not get off the couch. I slept all day Saturday, literally getting up to take a couple of bites of food and either laying back on the couch are going back to bed.  Sunday I woke up I felt better not 100% but I had some energy. The marks on my face were no different and now they are getting more painful burning, itching, still swollen and very painful to the touch.  4/20/21 nothing has gotten better. I went to the urgent care one of the PAs said it looks like it?s shingles.
Headache,  fever, muscle aches (especially my fingers) extreme exhaustion and brain fog. Tylenol is helping. Symptoms just started this morning

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 99-101 fever, headache, joint pain for all of the next day following vaccine. Two days following vaccine my arm pit of the arm I received the shot is hurting and swollen.

I took 1 Benandryl about 1 hour before the injection of the vaccine prior to leaving my home.  My son took me as I would anticipate some type of reaction given my history.  J&J was the one my doctor recommended in hopes that I could handle the response better and only need 1 dose. I had options to get pfizer or moderna, but my dr wanted J&J so I waited several weeks longer to get this one.  Within 10 minutes of having the injection, my  ears swelled up, and felt like I was on a bad plane and could not burst clear.  Then my throat on left side, the same side I got the shot swelled.  My face was full of red and rash and my son mentioned he was concerned how I looked.  I told him my symptoms and then took another Benadryl before we left the store. I told the pharmacist that I was having a reaction, they wanted to call 911-I said please no. I am used to having reactions and would want to see if I can manage it with Benadryl at home.  I came home and took my Alegra (as I take my alegra at night before bed to help with congestion).  Going forward every 2-3 hours I would take another benadryl rotating the time frames and slept as much as possible. It took several hours for the swelling to subside, longer than I was used to.  Over the next several days, I would have times when my ears, throat would swell, my face would be red and rashed, especially at night my face will get red, rash and ears and throat swell late at night. It waxes and wains depending on how I feel.   After the main allergic reaction of 12-24 hours later, I stared with the COVID symptoms, fever, chills, body ache, the joints that I have trouble with hurt so much more (knee, foot, arms, hands) I was so thankful I did not catch COVID. I don't think I would have survived. On Friday, March 19, 2021 was the first day I started to feel better except for the late night episodes of allergic reaction. I take Alegra or when needed Benadryl. It seems to lower my swelling response.
LAB_DATA: I did contact my GP, Dr to see if anything I needed to do.  None were requested
OTHER_MEDS: Alegra, 85 mg Vit C, 1000 mg (2-3 pills a day) Vit D, 5000 uc (1 pill daily) Calcium, 500 (1 pill daily) Fiber pills (2 pills) Probiotic 10,000 (1 pill every other day)
CUR_ILL: None -- I try to keep myself very healthy as I am limited with antibiotics and other meds to take.
HISTORY: Lyphodema,  Chronic orthopedic issues in arms, hand, knees and feet from various surgeries, varicous veins,  Severe Allergic response to meds,
PRIOR_VAX: Flu - 2020 - had minor reaction with body ache and swelling, nothing like this J&J
ALLERGIES: Many and many have a severe response usually  Aspirin, NSAIDS, PCN, Codeine, Kenalog, Tamiflu, Tylenol, Bupivacaine, Lidocaine, medrol dos packet, morphine, dilaudid, clindamycin, bactrim, cipro, clarithormycin, doxcycline, cymbalta, lyrica, Synvisc, dexamethosone, (general no steroids),  Triamterene-HCT2, Lasix, Nystatin cream.

After the 2nd shot, I felt a bit tired after about 6 hours. Then, at about 4:00 am (14 hours afterwards), I woke up with a very high feer of 103, my body ached everywhere and I had the chills. At first, I tried to take just ibprophen, but I started to throw everything up,including the medication. I still had all of these painful symptoms and no relief, so I had to go into an urgent care. Since they could not give me an IV, they gave me Zofran, so that I could stop vomiting and get medication for my high fever. Once that began to work, I was finally able to bring down the fever and chills. Though my fever did spike on and off for 2 days, it did eventually go down after a full day. I was extremely tired for approximately 2 days after. After day three, I was able to get back to normal activity.

I have also developed patches of very itchy rashes, that just started to pop up on my right ankle, stomach, and upper right thigh. I want to make sure it is not some adverse long-term effect of the shot.

The morning after the first dose of the Pfizer vaccine, my shoulders were incredibly tight. At 11 am that day, I had a muscle spasm on the lower left side of my back. I laid down and gradually throughout the day my entire back began to tighten up until I could barely move. At 4 pm I tried to stand and the pain was excruciating. I couldn't stand more than a few minutes without pain and laid back down. By 7 pm, I couldn't move at all. We called the paramedics to take me to the ER. At the ER, I was given medication to help manage the pain and prescribed pain meds at home. I was in bed and unable to move without help and excruciating pain for the next 5 days. I continued to have muscle spasms in my back while standing and sitting during that time. Since then, my mobility has begun to return slowly. I have seen a chiropractor several times, my doctor, had an x-ray done of my back (results were normal), PT several times, and request for an MRI was denied by Insurance. I continue to have soreness in my back and tightness in my shoulders almost 6 weeks after. 4 weeks after the vaccine, I had dizziness, nausea, and headaches. This lasted for 12 hrs and returned again 5 weeks after. I continue to have extreme fatigue halfway through my day doing way less than normal activities.

Narrative: 72 yo M that received dose #1 of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 2/26/2021 (Lot#:011A21A: Exp Date: 08/16/2021) and dose #2 of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 3/26/2021 (Lot#: 007B21A; Exp Date:09/08/2021). Most recent A1C prior to COVID-19 vaccination 8.0% on 2/2/2021 and established on metformin 850mg PO BID and glipizide 10mg PO BID. Following non-fasting lab appointment on 3/1/2021, serum glucose=626; provider advised patient to go to local ED or fire station if develops symptoms of hyperglycemia. Note documented on 3/16/2021, Patient presented to the emergency department based outpatient clinic with increased frequency of urination, polydipsia, but no other signs or symptoms of hyperglycemia, found to have hyperglycemia with metabolic acidosis, acute kidney injury and pseudo hyponatremia. At this time patient admitted to hospital for further monitoring, evaluation, and treatment of hyperosmolar nonketotic hyperglycemic state, with mild ketoacidosis and AKI. Pt treated with IV fluid rehydration with normal saline, started on sliding scale insulin. In addition, pt started on basal insulin glargine 10 units every evening. Pt then subsequently discharged (incomplete records). On 3/22/2021, patient obtained non-fasting lab work with serum glucose=504 and A1C=12.5%. Pt has been consulted to endocrinology based on rurality of patient and subsequent management of diabetes.

After I received my first dose I started to experience my first symptom on March 30, 2021. I noticed that I had a small lump on the left side of my rib cage beside my left breast which was about the size of a sausage link. The area wasn't painful, slightly tender to the touch and soft. By 4/3/21 the area has expanded to the upper portion of the scapula and it was no longer located on the side of my rib. It was about the size a pear and it was inflamed and very tender to the touch. I couldn't raise my arm and it was pertruding from my clothing and preventing me from sleeping at night on that side. By 4/5/21 the mass had turned into a different shape and direction and it was no longer just primarily on my scapula.. This current shape favored a boomerang and it started on my lower scapula and wrapped around my arm going directly into the middle of my arm pit.. It was about an 1.5 inches wide, inflamed, painful and wouldn't allow me to fully lift my arm or lay on it.. The mass was hard and didn't move, I visited a prompt care and they couldn't decipher what it was. I began to take tylenol and use cold compress and over a few days the mass began to decrease in size and I was able to increase my range of motion obtaining full extension on 4/17/21. The mass is now smaller than a pencil on 4/22/21 and hardly noticable but it was quite an experience.
ALLERGIES: Wheat, soy, dairy, cod fish, sweet potatoes, coconut, tomatoes

On 7 April, approx 9AM, pt. experienced a TIA (Transient Ischemic Attack or Mini-stroke).  Siblings became aware by 10:30, and by 11:45 he was at the ER.  His speech was extremely restricted and he was barely able to speak a few words.  Face was partially asymmetric, but gross and fine motor skills basically unaffected.  He could walk and write his name, follow commands to move arm and legs.  Underwent multiple tests including CAT scan, when no sign of bleed stroke confirmed.  At admittance, Stroke Scale score = 4.  By 3PM, speech started to return, and continued to return.  Continued tests with EEG, EKG, and TTE, but no source for TIA could be pinpointed. Unable to perform MRI due to embedded medical device. By next morning speech had almost returned to normal.  No physical restrictions noted on following day.  Discharged 6PM on 8 April.  Doctors unable to explain cause and could not comment on whether related to receiving vaccine a week prior.  Recovery seems to be complete with no negative lasting effects as of 22 April, 2021.
LAB_DATA: EEG, EKG, TTE, Cat scans on 7 and 8 April at Hospital
OTHER_MEDS: Kepra (generic), Aption, NaCl, Vitamin B complex and Vit D
CUR_ILL: No Illnesses.  But he fell and hit head resulting in stiches on Mar31.  Fall result of seizure

Normally I take a Coreg CR 20 mg @9am, and another one @9pm; blood pressure (BP) was well controlled for the last 5 years. The day of the 2nd COVID dose I started feeling malaise/weakness around 7-8pm. My BP was 188/106 (3 measurements average). Took the 9pm Coreg at 8pm; didn't feel improvement, my BP increased to 220/118. I took a Labetalol 100mg; in about 2-3 hrs my PB came down to 170/105 and I fell asleep. I woke up several times feeling sick. The next day my BP was higher than usual around 170/112 (in the morning I felt a bit better; but started to feel very sick again in the afternoon; it continued in the evening & during the night). I felt as if my heart was giving up. The only reason I did not go to Emergency was the fear I can get the COVID in the hospital.   THIS WAS A VERY SERIOUS, LIFE THREATENING EVENT; if I didn't have Labetalol in the house I believe I would be dead now.   Note: I did not panic, my pulse was around 66 the first day. The second day it was around 72.   There should be an investigation covering the side effects in people with a high BP history after the 2nd vaccine dose, to make sure their problems were not blamed on their health history. During the side effects/time frame I described, it seemed my BP medication did not have the effect it usually has on me.  I found it unacceptable that the only site reporting the spikes in BP as a COVID vaccine side effect was a hospital in another country; if there were such side effects reported by the date of my vaccine, they were not readily available for the public.   These heart problems could have been made much better if people like me knew of an increase in BP as adverse reaction to the vaccine's 2nd dose, so we could have been prepared, i.e. take the BP medication BEFORE the BP spikes up so much, so it doesn't reach critical values (especially in the conditions of malaise and general sickness given by the vaccine.)
HISTORY: Well controlled blood pressure (same treatment w Coreg 40mg/day for almost 5 years)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I just spent 14 hrs in the ER trying to treat, what I was sure to be, an ovarian cyst. The pain had been building over the past mo. I procrastinated going to the ER, because I wanted my 2nd dose b4 going, which was yesterday.    I had exams, pelvic, ultrasounds, Cat scans, labs, etc & they found nothing. I can barely walk without doubling over.  4 wks ago I had an L-5 block & trigger point injections with steroids, due to inflamed nerve roots, & inflamed L thigh. 1 wk later, I had my 1st shot, L arm. Within days my abdomen began hurting mildly, but I thot it'd subside. It never occurred to me that it could be related to the vaccine. 2 wks later, it was unbearable & I thot it an ovarian cyst. I waited for my 2nd shot appt, b4 going to ER, in case I was hospitalized. I didn't want to ruin my 2nd dose, as I have lung issues.   ER Dr said, I had "undetermined inguinal pain". Then, I found a study about women, hormonal changes & the vaccine. I saw that lymph nodes can get inflamed after a vaccine.   Now, I think I had a vulnerable area on my L side, then rec'd steroids L side, which lowered my immune system. Next, I rec'd my 1st shot L side, & my "inguinal lymph node" on L side became inflamed. It got progressively worse, & now my 2nd dose was yesterday, also on my L side, & has aggrivated it even more.   Tomorrow I see my pcp.  It feels exactly like my ovary's swollen, & the inguinal lymph node's located right in the same place, so after all tests have been negative, I suspect a connection & I'll discuss with pcp for more testing & treatment.
LAB_DATA: UCLA ER: 4/21/2021  > 2 types of ultrasound  > contrast CAT Scan  > pelvic exams > labs, blood, urine  = all negative.   I didn't see article about lymph nodes until after discharge.

Extreme weakness, inability to sit upright for extended period of time, extreme fatigue with walking short distances, diarrhea/loss of bowel control, extremely pail skin, cold extremities, low blood pressure.  Started approximately 27 hours after vaccine and continued to get worse.  Dr. was consulted and diagnosed Shy-Dragers Syndrome related to Dementia as a possibility.  We were to increase salt intake and observe for worsening.  Patient began showing improvement after about 5 days.  Was taken to hospital ER for UTI evaluation per Dr.; no UTI present but bloodwork showed the need for a two-unit blood transfusion.
LAB_DATA: Hospital (03/11/2021):  Catheterization/urinalysis:  No UTI.  Chest x-ray:  no issues.  Bloodwork:  Hemoglobin 6.5, Platelet count 1017.  Abdominal scan:  Upper GI abnormality; unable to determine type.  Two units of whole blood were transfused.  Was suggested by hospital staff that vaccine could have raised her normally elevated platelet count (due to the Thrombocythemia) to a level that had caused internal bleeding.  But to rule out upper GI bleeding, scope evaluation was recommended.  Transferred to Hospital for scope procedure; unsuccessful due to Zinkers pouch of the esophagus.  Hemoglobin had increased to 10.6, and platelet count was much lower.  (03/12/2021)  Throughout hospitalization, Hemoglobin gradually increased and platelet count held steady at the lower levels that were more typical of her normal count.  These two items were tested over every 10 days over the next month at Health Care.   Hemoglobin increased to 11.7 and platelet counts ranged from the 740's to 780's.  This seems to indicate that her blood loss was not from bleeding from a chronic upper GI issue but rather related to an isolated incident such as the COVID vaccine elevating her platelet count to over one million.

I took the FIRST dose of the Moderna vaccine this Tuesday on the  20th of April at 11:30 AM. Around 10:00 PM Wednesday I have been feeling short of breath. This feeling has persisted throughout the entire day of Thursday and I continue to feel the same way (I think it has slightly worsened). I can breath, but I am completely unable to take a full, deep breath. I sometimes can achieve a full deep breath but it's completely at random. I find myself trying to forcefully take a deep breath but can't seem to fully fill my lungs how I normally am able to.  Additionally, my throat feels mildly swollen/sore, starting from the back of my mouth and down my esophagus. The lowest point of my esophagus at which I feel the soreness/mild swelling is near the center of my chest.  I think my shortness of breath is progressively, and slowly worsening, but its hard to tell for certain. Some of the muscles around my back are beginning to feel uncomfortable due to me constantly trying to forcefully achieve a full and deep breath.

Concurrent medical conditions included Asthma and Allergy. Concomitant products included EPINEPHRINE (EPIPEN) for Allergy, ALBUTEROL SULFATE for Asthma.    On 12-Mar-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 12-Mar-2021, the patient experienced the first episode of ANAPHYLACTIC REACTION (anaphylactic reaction) (seriousness criterion medically significant). On 09-Apr-2021, the patient experienced the second episode of ANAPHYLACTIC REACTION (anaphylactic reaction) (seriousness criterion medically significant). On 11-Apr-2021, last episode of ANAPHYLACTIC REACTION (anaphylactic reaction) had resolved.        The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown.       The patient experienced an anaphylactic reaction of constricted throat, face and neck turning red, tingling and numbness in her face and throat, red bumps on her face and throat, and her face felt like it was burning. She used her EpiPen and it wasn't enough (didn't improve the reaction), so she went to the emergency room. They gave 2 prednisone tabs and prescribed prednisone and gave her IV saline and antihistamine. They released her 2 hours later. Her doctor advised her against getting the second dose. After the patient recovered from initial anaphylactic reaction on 12Mar2021, she had 2 episodes of anaphylactic reaction on 09APR2021, requiring the use of two EpiPens, Benadryl, Prednisone, and albuterol. On 10APR2021 at 0100 another anaphylactic reaction requiring EpiPen, Benadryl, Prednisone, and Albuterol. And at 4pm another anaphylactic reaction requiring Benadryl, EpiPen, and albuterol. Currently she has recovered. Different practices do it differently / It's confusing and it's not clear; Different practices do it differently / It's confusing and it's not clear; This case was reported by a nurse via call center representative and described the occurrence of product label confusion in a patient who received Men ACWY-CRM NVS (Menveo) for prophylaxis. Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not applicable for this report. The nurse asked about recommendations of use of Menveo for patients with Sickle Cell Disease. The instruction were like dose 1 at age 8 weeks: 4-dose series at 2, 4, 6, 12 months, Dose 1 at age 36 months: 3 or 4 dose series (dose 2 and dose 3 if applicable at least 8 weeks after previous dose until a dose is received at age 7 months or older, followed by an additional dose at least 12 weeks later and after age 12 months), Dose 1 at age 723 months: 2 dose series (dose 2 at least 12 weeks after dose 1 and after age 12 months) and Dose 1 at age 24 months or older 2 dose series at least 8 weeks apart. Some offices interpreting that can choose between all four option and some interpret as first option was the recommendation and the other three were the catch up recommendation if did not start on time. Upon medical information callback to the reporter, she states she cut and pasted centers for disease control recommendations into email to GSK (GlaxoSmithKline).  Different practices do it differently, asked what are the differences between the recommendations. It was confusing and was not clear on your part and on Centers for Disease Control part and therefore not clear on Health and Human Services part and wanted to clarify on the intention so there was not misinterpretation, which led to product label confusion and circumstance or information capable of leading to medication error. The reporter consent to follow up.

I had a nasty zit on the back of my neck, popped it, and my immune response was extreme. Initial: Itching and burning through my neck and shoulders, and swollen lymph nodes in neck and collarbone. I began sweating at night profusely and losing weight. I have had a lot of trouble sleeping. These symptoms continued in 24-48 hour cycles of flare ups until 04/19/2021 but finally seem to be abating. Progression: secondary symptoms appeared over the course of the month such as full body joint soreness, weakness, stiffness, stabbing pains (in the neck, arms, chest, and abdomen), blood pressure spikes, dry/sore throat, dry eyes, difficulty swallowing. Symptoms are similar to arthritis or other autoimmune diseases. Night sweats continue but are lighter. Weight loss continues but slower. Sleeping remains irregular.

My mom found me about 10 seconds later confirming I wasn?t out for that long, but she was slapping my face and talking to me and I was unaware. She reported that my eyes were open. When I came to I was having cold sweats, I was clammy, and my ears were ringing. I was very scared and I don?t know what happened to me. I felt like I was dreaming when I woke up, but once my Tylenol kicked in I felt better. But it still was a very strange out of body experience.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 4/14/2021 - Within a half hour of the shot, he could barely lift his arm which we know is a normal part of the vaccine.  As the night went on, it gradually worsened and he was unable to use his arm to complete his job as a custodian.  The next morning he was unable to move his up up and down and complained that they may have given him the shot in the wrong place of his muscle.  After comparing where the shot should have been we determined it was probably just part of the process and he continued to take Motrin and Tylenol.   4/22/2021 - After more than a week he is still unable to raise his arm half way as from his muscle to the top of his shoulder is pain.  We contacted our family physician who indicated she had not heard of the pain from the shot lingering for more than a few days.   She advised him for the next 48 to take 1000 MG of Tylenol and 800 MG of Motrin for the next 48 hours.  4/23/2021 -  We are currently following her advice however it does not seem to be helping the pain at this time.

I unfortunately have some concerns after getting the vaccine, and am hoping to hear both from someone who can disprove my concerns and any mamas to be with similar issues. I had a 14-week us and baby was measuring within a few days of my predicted due date. I got the first Pfizer shot at about 15 weeks. Sore arm and mild fever for two days, nbd. Second shot at 19 weeks. Mild fever for four days. Also no big deal. But I just had my 20 week us yesterday and am now measuring about three weeks behind. Had to follow up with maternal/fetal at the hospital for more analysis, and they confirmed I am measuring below 5th percentile for 20 weeks. Anatomically, everything looks okay, no defects, and they cannot find a source for the stunted growth, so this is good news. But I?m just to ?wait and see? for three weeks now how my growth trajectory looks. Given the ironic timeline of the growth delay with the timing of the vaccines I asked the doc today whether it?s pure coincidence or possibly related, and she assured me there?s no reason to believe it?s related, but she can understand my concern given the timeline. I understand my growth issue could be related to any number of things, but I can?t shake the coincidence of the vaccine timing with the growth slowing. I will be returning to Hospital in three weeks for a follow up on the IUGR issue and an updated growth projection.
LAB_DATA: Anatomy sonogram at OB-GYN office,  4/20. Anatomy sonogram follow up at hospital, 4/21.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 30 minutes after receiving the 2nd dose my left elbow  hurt terribly (joint pain). After about another 30 minutes the external skin on my left elbow hurt as of it were scraped open. Evening of 2nd vaccine I became very exhausted. By the next morning  my left arm's injection  she hurt, I was exhausted, my body hurt, I was sick on my stomach, and I had a general sense of feeling "off". The symptoms worsened and I had to stay in bed for approximately 38 hours. On 4/11/2021 I began to improve but still remained nauseous and exhausted and my left arm still hurt tremendously. On 4/12/2021 my symptoms continued to improve, although the nausea, extreme fatigue, and arm pain persisted. By the evening of 4/13/2021 I began to worsen. By the morning of 4/15/2021 I felt horrible. My fatigue had gotten worse, my body was aching (joints/muscle/nerves), my elbow had started to hurt again, I had multiple migraines, and I began to experience brain fog for the first time. I was very nauseous and had ab overall feeling of "just feeling not right and feeling awful in a way that was hard to explain." My injection site began hurting again. This all frightened me and I made an appointment with my GP. Today is 4/23/2021 and I still have the following symptoms: injection site hurts badly (I cannot sleep on that side), nausea (inconsistent, it goes away then returns with intensity), joint/body pain if I exert myself (I exercise regularly and have no longer been able to do that since receiving the vaccine), elbow pain, and brain fog (for me it feels like I am spaced out and I cannot recall words).   A concern that I have is my mother has severe Sarcoidosis. I do not have it but I feel it is important for researchers to consider family and patient history.
OTHER_MEDS: Synthroid, Flonase, Vitamin D, Ubrelvy (as needed, not daily)

I had my first vaccination for COVID-19 on March 31, 2021. 14 days after that vaccination, I had a minor outbreak of SJS but that cleared prior to my second vaccination. My second vaccination was April 21, 2021 at 2:51pm and I had no reaction for the first 36 hours. I woke up at 3am on Friday, April 23 with swelling, itching, burning lips with blisters which is a symptom of SJS so I can only assume that the vaccination is causing the outbreak. I am currently seeking medical attention from my dermatologist for treatment. I also have blisters on my gums and it is extremely painful. I am reporting the adverse reaction but I do not know if the SJS will continue to escalate as in 2011, I was treated multiple times in the emergency room.
LAB_DATA: There is no test for SJS (Stevens-Johnson Syndrome). I discovered I had SJS after going through a clinical trial for a Hepatitis C treatment (sofusbuvir). Eight weeks into that trial, I had a severe reaction that escalated to sloughing skin on the lips, gums and cheeks.
CUR_ILL: minor outbreak of SJS 2 weeks after the first vaccination but had cleared prior to the second
HISTORY: I am in a chronic pain management program and I have recurring SJS (Stevens-Johnson Syndrome) that has occurred multiple times since 2011.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had the vaccine n Sunday, Tuesday morning I woke up with a very tight feeling across my chest/ rib cage area, particularly on my right side, underarm, under breast area. I also had some weakness in my left arm where the shot was given. The tightness in my chest was not affecting my ability to breath, I was able to go on my usual daily hour-long walk but it was concerning me enough for a call with a Dr. I had spent the day before (Monday) using a wood pellet BBQ so I though maybe the issue was related to smoke. The Dr prescribed a salbutamol inhaler which I have used before for seasonal allergies but that didn't really d anything to help with the tight feeling. The feeling of tightness remained all week (and still does to some extent 11 days later).  On the Friday I noticed a small dark spot, approx 2mm,  a bit like a blood blister on the back of my right thigh. I have had these before fairly infrequently, and I see a dermatologist once a year for a check up and they are not concerned, and they usually go away on their own. But, the combination of a new blood spot and the continued tight feeling across my chest had me concerned enough to call my regular Dr's office.  I was also feeling occasional sporadic aches in my legs in varying places. I spoke to a practice nurse who was very reassuring that she had spoken to many other patients that had also been experiencing chest tightness that had gone on for days after the Janssen vaccine, so after that I felt less concerned about the symptoms. I am still experiencing the tightness in my chest which has affected my shoulders and neck with what feels like muscle tension, and also been accompanied by some mild headaches at the sides of my head. I was pretty anxious about getting the vaccine which is not something I usually struggle with and on the Tuesday after the vaccine I felt particularly irrational and also very tired.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitafusion Women's Gummy Daily Vitamin x 2 daily ForestLeaf Quercetin Bromelain x 2 daily (for seasonal allergies)
CUR_ILL: None  Had  annual physical onApril 2nd, no issues, didn't require bloodwork
ALLERGIES: Wheat Seasonal allergies Some animals, cats especially.

I received my second vaccination around 10:00 AM.  I waited 15 minutes in the pharmacy to make sure I didn't have any negative reactions before leaving.  I felt fine at 15 minute mark.  As I was driving home, I did feel a little off and my arm was a little sore on injection side.  All of a sudden, out of nowhere, my vision started to turn black starting from outside and tunneling in while I was driving 35 mph.  I didn't have much warning that I was going to black out but I did.  Before blacking out I tried to put my car in park out of reflex while going 35 then everything went dark.  When I awoke I thought I was going to wake up in bed.  I had a whole dream but realized quickly I was in my car then everything came back to me. Instead of the car being in park it was in reverse and I reversed the car into two other cars on the road.  Luckily no one was hurt.  I am very shaken up.  I am a healthy 36 year old and tolerated first does just fine.  People need to have others drive them after receiving vaccination.  If I was on the highway or had my kids in the car things could have been much different.
LAB_DATA: The police, fire squad and ambulance came to the crash.  I had an EKG in the ambulance and quick physical and everything was back to normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I started to develop Bell's palsy ~24hrs after receiving the vaccine (got the vaccine Saturday 1pm, noticed symptoms periodically through Sunday). I recognized the early symptoms from one previous episode of Bell's palsy ~7mo ago (knot next to/under nose with the feeling of tightness and slight loss of feeling). I took 800mg ibuprofen every 3 hours upon the advice of my aunt, a nurse practitioner, to hopefully stop it before it progressed to full palsy, but on Wednesday woke up with facial droop and numbness primarily focused around the nose and upper lip on the right side. I went to Urgent Care facility, and received Prednisone for the Bell's palsy and Valacyclovir to cover in case it was a viral infection that flared when my immune system dropped after receiving the vaccine. The facial numbness is getting better but is not yet resolved (Friday). I am in the process of scheduling a follow up with a neurologist.
OTHER_MEDS: Zyrtec, glucosamine, melatonin (daily), vitamin D, magnesium, cranberry extract, probiotic (every other day)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: She has a history of Bipolar II, dx about 2 years ago. She has been in counseling for the past 5 years. She just changed from effexor to lexapro about 1 month ago. She has been on abilify 10mg for the past ~6months.  On 4/8/21 she went to bed around 11pm and awoke on 4/9 around 8:30am.   She had her JJ covid vaccine on 4/9/21. She had 2 handfuls of goldfish crackers on the way to her vaccine appointment around 11am. She had ~6-8oz of water when she awoke. She arrived at the Clinic on campus. She sat down for ~5 minutes and then the staff came to get her. She had the shot administered in left deltoid. When she first felt the pain her vision started to go black and she felt like she was going to pass out. She denies feeling hot or dizzy prior to event. Her vision went completely black, then when she "came to" she was bent over in her chair with arms drawn up to body and fists clenched. Immediately her body relaxed and she felt very confused. She was told she just had a seizure - bend forward and had whole body shaking for ~30 seconds.   She felt extremely nauseated and had some dry heaving. Someone helped her to the floor and put up her legs. She was told she looked very pale. She felt much better within 5 minutes. Vitals were checked and were stable. She was given granola bar to eat and drank ~12oz of water. No one sided weakness, no incontinence, no tongue bite. She stayed there for ~45 minutes for monitoring. Someone walked her to her car, asked her if she was ok, and then she drove herself home.   Of note, the room she was in was warm and they were going to open doors to get some air. She was not ill or tired at the time.   After the event she drove for 5 minutes to her home. Once in her room she felt extremely tired and then slept until 7pm (~6-7 hours). She then called Mom. Mom reports that patient sounded different on the phone. Speech was slow and she seemed "off." Mom drove to her and was at her room by around 7:40pm. At that time, patient looked very pale to Mom. Mom took her home, gave her chicken soup. She did not have an appetite. She just wanted to go to sleep. Mom tried to have her stay up until around 10pm. She had ~8oz of water and then went to bed. She slept through the night. She awoke the next morning and reports that her brain felt like it hurt to work. She had chills, body pain, shakiness during the day on 4/10/21. This was easily managed by tylenol q4.   Of note, she did have covid19 in 8/2020. She was ill for ~1 week with lack of smell/taste, febrile, shakiness, headache.  She had an odd event on 4/19/21 while giving a presentation at school. She had sudden onset of left pinky numbness/tingling with radiated up the side of her forearm. This lasted ~1-2 minutes. However, her left arm hurt for a few hours afterward. She denies any fatigue after event.  She has a Mirena IUD. She smokes nicotine via vape numerous times per day. She smoke weed up to 3X/day but not every day. She drinks beer a few days per week.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I woke up at 3:10 am feeling cold and chilling. I took by temperature and it was 98.4. I normally have a temperature of 97.1 - 97.7. I take it daily multiple times. My hands were cold. When I got up and started moving around I didn't have any more chills. When I got up at 6:30 am. I just didn't feel well in general. Slight feeling of sniffles, congestion.  I would get some aches that went away in a few seconds. They were at various points in my body, knee joints, muscles, and my head. They were simply a nuisance. I felt tired all day. My blood pressure was up 15-20 points on both numbers during the day. I've told my doctor when my blood pressure is higher, I'm having more aches and pains as though I'm fighting a virus. I tolerated the symptoms most of the day, letting my immune system try to work it out. My symptoms seemed worse at 5:45 pm, so I took two ibuprofen. My temperature was 98.9 at that point. The highest it's been. All my symptoms got better until 1:15 am. I woke up feeling like I was chilling, but not as bad as yesterday, so I took two more ibuprofen. I feel 50% better today and haven't taken any ibuprofen. Here is the really strange part. I had these exact symptoms and similar temperature ranges twic last year. In July and October I think. I didn't get tested last year because they were minor symptoms. They were just nuisance symptoms. I took ibuprofen right away last year.  I followed the masking guidelines, social distancing, etc. So, is it just coincidence I had similar symptoms last year two times, that I had when I getting the inactive Moderna vaccine? I had no reaction to the first shot.  I just wanted to provide the information in case it is helpful. Very strange. I expect no other symptoms in a couple of days.
HISTORY: Need allergy shots once a month. Taken those for 2 years. Amlodipine for blood pressure that is slowing inching up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Upon receiving the vaccine, I immediately fainted (vasovagal syncope). I was unconscious for ~15-20 seconds. My apartment-mate who came with me for the shot laid me down on the floor until I could sit up again without feeling dizzy (~15 min). I also had pretty serious bruising at the injection site for ~9 days following the injection and my arm was swollen and painful (although this is a pretty normal side-effect).

4 days (4/20/2021) post vaccination pain in right calf was experienced. As the pain did not resolve over the next week and felt similar to a DVT experienced post a spinal fusion in 2018 I consulted, on 4/16/2021, with the vascular surgeon, who treated my post surgery DVT in 2018 . He performed an ultrasound and identified a clot in my right calf. On 4/21/2021 he prescribed a course of Eliquis (initial dose 20 mg per day) to resolve the clot. As of today (4/23/2021) the pain has lessened but not resolved. In addition to the DVT I experienced a significant level of fatigue for 3 days post the vaccination. While the fatigue has lessened it has not completely resolved.
LAB_DATA: Ultrasound 4/16/2021 - clot identified in right calf
HISTORY: Ongoing low-level nerve pain post spinal fusion in 2018

My arm swelled slightly, was warm at the injection site and ached about 12 hrs after the injection.  The leg aches lasted about 2 days, the arm ache lasted about 1 day and the slight arm swelling lasted about 6 days... Reason for my reporting:  I had an annual eye exam 4/14/21 where a retinal scan was done.  The optometrist saw some blood spots in my left eye and referred me to an ophthalmologist.  Ophthalmologist performed additional scans and tests including a Fluroescein angiography and determined I have BRVO (Branch Retinal Vein Occlusion) which is a series of blot clots in small vessels of the eye's main vein.  He did not say it could be a result of the vaccine but I have no risk factors associated with getting BRVO.  Since it is not affecting my vision yet, the doctor wants to monitor it in 3 months to make sure it has not worsened.  Since the Janssen vaccine was put on hold for causing other types of blot clots in women in my age group, I am wondering if the vaccine caused the blood clots in my eye.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: T+ 4 to 6 hours: mild fever, fatigue. T+ 1 days: mild fever continues, hot flashes begin, mostly at night interrupting sleep. T+ 2 days - 7 days: fever subsides, hot flashes increase in intensity significantly, continuing to interfere with sleep. Other possible androgenic symptoms begin to arise: change in body odor, sex drive, motivations, appetite. T+ 7 days till current: previous symptoms of days 2-7 continue, extremely gradual onset headache begins one night. Making sure to rule out hydration and electrolyte imbalance expecting headache to be gone in the morning after sleep, I found that it was only worse and that an interpolation of the two pain points from when I went to sleep and woke up would have created a almost imperceptibly gradual but linear increase between the two points. The headache was of a type I had never had before, located in the center of my head just barely dorsal to the spinal insertion. It felt deeper than any headache I had had before which usually occur in the frontal lobe/neocortex zone. I do not regularly suffer headaches getting maybe a couple per year. Once I recognized androgenic involvement and the headache were continuing I took myself to the ER where I was evaluated and despite presenting with continuous hypertension and the symptoms mentioned above, I could not get them to perform a estrogen test and they let me leave with hypertension without any investigation. I'm returning today to their urgent care facility to try again to get my estrogen levels checked. I had left a message on the phone line of VAERS prior to the original ER visit but had not heard back from anyone so I felt it was prudent to file a written report here.
LAB_DATA: Standard blood panel and FMV scan to rule out large clots or bleeds.

Patient received his first Moderna COVID vaccine. While he was waiting the 15 minutes he started to feel pressure behind his eyes, started sweating profusely, felt dizzy, and nauseous.  I had the patient go into the IMZ room where I had him sit down.  I took his blood pressure. His heart rate was 55 bpm and his blood pressure was around 110/70.  He was not having any trouble breathing or had any signs of anaphylaxis (swelling of throat, tongue, lipps, etc). I had him remain seated and talked to him for 5 minutes. He felt like he was starting to come out of it and we took his blood pressure again.  His heart rate and gone back up to 65 and his blood pressure was around 135/75.  I had the patient remain seated for another 5-10 minutes.  Took his bp again and the numbers were similar to the second one that was previously mentioned.  He wanted to stand up and see how he was feeling.  He stood up right outside the pharmacy for another 15 minutes and said that he felt back to normal.  I explained that in the previous case where this happened to a woman they recommended she have someone drive her home and I recommended he do the same.  He seemed to think he was fine and I believe he was planning to drive himself home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Seizure - I have never had a seizure before and there is no history of epilepsy in my family. I had the Janssen vaccine shot at around 5PM on Thursday and felt mostly fine on Friday. On Friday night around 10:00, I was standing talking to one of my friends in the living room when I had a blackout seizure without any warning. The seizure only lasted about 30-45 seconds, and then I became conscious again. It took me about 5-10 minutes to become completely aware and able to stand up. I have never had a seizure before and have not had one since then.  Later the following week, I did have a couple of hours where I felt extremely dizzy and lightheaded, but it went away without another seizure. This is also not typical for me.
LAB_DATA: I have had bloodwork and a CT scan of my skull to ensure there aren't any other issues that could have caused the seizure.  All of these tests came back normal.

I was diagnosed with "Palandromic Rheumatism" in the fall of 2019 and started on Hydroxycloroquine in November 2019.   I had little join pain in the 15 months following the start of that medication.     I had dose one of the Pfizer vaccine on February 16, 2021 and did not have any immediate reaction.  However, my joint inflammation (related to "Palandromic Rheumatism") flared up within a week or so of the first dose.  I called my rheumatiologist and asked whether it could be related to the vaccine and received a "possibly".   I proceeded to get the second dose.     The joint pain has been significant and has persisted.  On March 31, I was prescribed prednisone.   Although there was some immediate relief, the pain has continued to come and go in my wrists.     My prescription will end in a few days and we shall see what happens.    My situation is tolerable and I am glad to be vaccinated.  However, my concern is that autoimmune disorders are agragavated by the vaccine.  I have a friend who has a similar situation tho much more seriously.   He had not considered that it might be related to the vaccine.   I just want to make sure the CDC is aware of these kinds of possible impacts, has the available data from those who have received the vaccine,  and can inform the public and the professional community and hopefully have some suggestions on preventive measures to avoid these kinds of reactions.

Received my shot, talked with the nurse for about a minute or two afterwards in the back and she informed me that i needed to wait 10-15 minutes before i left. i go to the waiting room and set my alarm for 10 minutes. i texted my mother i was done and leaving  to go back home soon and that my second appt was on May 11. she texted back, i responded once again that i will call her when i get home in just over an hour.  Since i had no idea what to expect if something "did go wrong", i picked up my packet of information i received prior to my shot and started browsing through. i saw the possible serious side effects column and started to go through the list. At the time, about 5-6 mins now afterwards of my shot, i had no difficulty breathing, i did have a little tingling in my tongue, i read "a fast heartbeat", and put my hand on my chest and asked myself, IS MY HEART GOING FASTER? i looked at the paper again and put my hand back on my chest, and that was the last thing i remember until i was brought back to conscious by the nurses and doctors. i was told the guy in the waiting room ran after i passed out. when i came back to they walked me into the back, i was dizzy and profusively sweating and was drenched from head to toe , shirt and pants were SOAKED in sweat, they took my vitals for the next 40 minutes (3 or 4 times) i dont remember it too clearly until i started coming back to. Blood pressure was up and down and i was white as a ghost, they gave me fluids and i hung out until i felt superbly better about 40 minutes later. Then on my drive home, i had to pull over again, because i was getting light headed and felt like i was going to vomit. made it home, 90 minutes later, took a baby aspirin and slept the rest of the afternoon for about 5/6 hours before waking back up to eat some dinner.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: When giving patient the second dose of Moderna COVID vaccine the needle was not properly attached to the syringe.  Some of the vaccine was injected but most of it ran down his arm.  Per the direction of the CDC we decided to give a repeat of the second dose in the patient's right arm since we assumed less that half of the initial dose was administered.  CDC guidelines listed below:  If a lower-than-authorized dose volume is administered for any of the currently authorized vaccines, adhere to the following interim recommendation:  If more than half of the dose was administered, do not repeat the dose. If the dose given in error is the first dose, administer the second dose at the recommended interval of 28 days. If this dose is the second dose, the series is complete, and no additional doses are needed.  If less than half of the dose was administered or the proportion of the dose cannot be estimated, administer the authorized dose immediately in the opposite arm. If the dose given in error is the first dose, administer the second dose at the recommended interval of 28 days from the date of receipt of the valid dose (not the date of receipt of the erroneous dose).
LAB_DATA: The patient was asked to wait for 30 minutes instead of 15 minutes just to make sure he was okay.  I checked with him after 30 minutes and he was feeling fine.  He went ahead and left the building

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received first dose of Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine, lot #EL9264, on 1/30/2021 at 1300. Patient has a history of allergies to Bactrim (hives), Clindamycin (unknown), nitrofurantoin (rash), penicillins (unknown), yellow dyes (hives), and azithromycin (unknown). When asked, patient states all of her allergies result in a rash treated with Benadryl--has not experienced anaphylactic shock or any life-threatening reactions. Patient was in waiting area and noticed that she felt flushed. Patient was brought back to exam room and examined by pharmacist and nurse. Erythema present at injection site, down arm, on neck, and face. Skin was flat and warm. Patient reported feeling anxious, but no nausea, dizziness, shortness of breath, or other symptoms. No swelling was noted in extremities or in lips or tongue. Blood pressure was 170/110 and heart rate was 130 bpm. Patient was given diphenhydramine 75 mg PO (was offered 50 mg but patient reported she typically takes 75 mg for past allergic reactions) and asked to stay for 30 more minutes. After 30 minutes, blood pressure decreased to 150/90 (pt has documented history of white coat syndrome), skin was less erythematous and the area of redness decreased. Asked patient if a family member could be called to pick her up; patient declined stating she lives just a few minutes away. Patient was instructed to seek emergent care if she develops difficulty breathing or other signs of anaphylaxis.
