SYMPTOM_TEXT: Date and time adverse event started: 3/10/2021 at approx. 12:30pm, a few moments after rcvding the vaccine. Pt reported that a few moments of rcvding the vaccine she felt pressure in her whole head, ears were clogged up, and had lumps in her throat; these symptoms lessen as the days goes by and she felt better by day 3. On day 4 (3/13/2021), pt reported she felt like she had a bad cold which turned into bronchitis and that lasted for 2 weeks that was accompanied by symptoms of stuffy head, stuffed up sinus and drainage, had low grade fever, and coughed up phlegm). Pt reported that she have history of tinnitus and post-nasal drips, the ringing in her left ear and the post-nasal drip was still ongoing prior to rcvding the COVID vaccine and these symptoms seems to have been exacerbated after she got the vaccine because she felt like it has gotten worse. Pt reported that she took otc Mucinex and Claritin on the 5th or 6th day from rcvding the vaccine. She went to see her PCP and got a chest x-ray (results: negative for any infections). Pt also reported she got tested twice for COVID-19 on 3/17/2021 & 3/23/2021 (results on both dates: negative). Pt reported that her PCP had advised her against getting the second dose. Advised pt that per her ADEs these are not a contraindication to getting the 2nd dose per CDC guidelines and per consulted Dr. The decision to get the second dose is up to her and her PCP. Advised pt that there is not knowing if the 2nd dose will make her tinnitus worse or if she will experience any ADEs. Also advised per CDC guidelines, "if it is not feasible to adhere to the recommended interval, the second dose of BioNTech COVID-19 vaccines may be scheduled for administration up to 6 weeks (42 days) after the first dose. There are currently limited data on efficacy of mRNA COVID-19 vaccines administered beyond this window. If the second dose is administered beyond these intervals, there is no need to restart the series". 4/18-Patient feeling much better, symptoms have resolved with the exception of weakness and fatigue. Patient has taken Advil to help alleviate migraine. No longer has migraines. Caller called back to adv that she is still having tinnitus and post nasal drip from the 1st shot.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin D3 daily Ibuprofen PRN Ativan PRN  Tums PRN  Gas-X PRN

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt presented to the ED from home for b/l lower extremity swelling x 2 weeks. She was reportedly in her recliner for approximately 12-18 hrs prior to being brought in via EMS. In the ED her b/l LE extremity was cold to touch and mottled. Her toes were white and nail beds blue. No pulses were found on Doppler on either extremity. She was also noted to be in a.fib with RVR. Doppler of LE showed extensive occlusive thrombus. Bedside echo showed the RV severely dilated with mobile thrombus and EF 20-25%. Given these findings there is a very high probability of massive PE, however given current situation of AKI and instability CT was unable to be performed. She was given TPA and admitted to ICU. Pt was started heparin gtt, as well as levophed and dobutamine for obstructive and cardiogenic shock as her troponin, kidney function, lactate and liver function all were elevated.  Of note pt lives in a hoarding situation and lives a sedentary lifestyle and reportedly only gets up from recliner to use the bathroom. Pt also has a 96 pack year history but was noted in her medical chart  to have quit smoking in 2017.
LAB_DATA: all test performed 4/22-23: Dopplers and Duplexes of bilateral lower extremities, echocardiogram, EKG, CXR CBC, CMP, Lactic Acid, ABG/VBG, PT/INR, PTT, Anti-Xa, Troponin, ProTBNP, Blood cultures, UA, Urine culture, TSH, A1C
HISTORY: hypothyroidism, hyperlipidemia, ex-smoker, obesity, pt reported irregular heartbeat previously but no known diagnosis of A fib  pt unable to elaborate at time of admission d/t clinical condition

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 3/8/21 65 y/o M received his first Covid-19 vaccine (Moderna) and states on 4/2/2021 he had a myocardial infarction with 2 stents placed. He discharged to home and was doing very well. Tuesday, 4/6/2021, he received the second Covid vaccine. The following morning, he had pain in his right ankle. It progressed and involved his left foot and ankle.  Over the next few days his pain progressed to involve his legs, but stopped at the knees. He had leg weakness and associated diarrhea, fever and chills. He thought his symptoms would pass and tried to wait it out over the weekend. When he awoke on Monday morning, 4/12/21, he could not move his feed. He went to the ER and was diagnosed with Guillain Barre Syndrome.. He received 5 doses of IVIG with very good response. Patient states his leg strength is improving, but is not back to baseline. His arms are unaffected by his Guillain-Barre. He is in Rehabilitation now.

MethyiPERDNISoline tablets 6 day dose from 6 tablets first day decreasing 1 tablet each day until gone. ? Triamcinalone 0.01% to put on rash ? Allegra  180 mg take one each morning ? April 14 ? feet looked like I had Portwine stains (birthmarks) on them and feet and hands              still swollen Fri. April 16 ? husband had an appointment with our regular Dr. at the Clinic.  We mentioned my rash and talked to him about having my 2nd dose.  He               said, ?Absolutely NOT! Not with this type of a reaction to the first one!?   He had me              stay on the Allegra and Pepcid but he also put me on  *HydrOXYzine Hydrocholride 50               mg tablets every 6 hrs.  I have not been able to take them every six hrs because they              ?knock me out? and I have other responsibilities.  I do take 50 mg about 9 p.m. and               3 a.m. daily. Sat. April 17 ? low grade fever all day but fever didn?t spike and I didn?t  have chills Fri. April 23-  17 days later?I still have a rash though it is slowly going away.  The rash on my                stomach is very light.  I no longer look like I have Portwine stains on my feet and the               swelling is gone.  I am still taking Allegra and Pepcid daily with the 2 doses of                HydrOXYzine 50 mg at night.  I am not using the lotion because Dr. said to                use it 14 days then off for 14 days and then on for 14 days.  It took us a little while to figure out what was wrong and then by husband decided to have it documented and to see if it was safe for me to have my second vaccine.  ***I have pictures to substantiate what my reaction looked like and the dates and times.

On 4/18/21, it was reported that the patient had a seizure following the 2nd dose of Pfizer vaccine.  This is a 19 year old female patient with a known history of a seizure disorder.  She has been under the care of a neurologist x 6 years, is not on any seizure medications, and no diagnosis made.  She reports she has a seizure every two weeks, which are triggered by anxiety/stressful events.  On this day, 3 minutes after received the 2nd dose in the supine position, she fell unconscious and developed eyelid and arm twitching.  Vitals signs remained stable.  MD described seizure as 'starting as a sleep state, moving to slight twitching, then tonic clonic.  Duration of seizure symptoms was 12 minutes. '  The patient regained consciousness, symptoms resolved, and patient was discharged home with family following increased observation.  No medication treatment needed.  Upon chart review, it was identified that she has a similar reaction following her 1st Pfizer dose.  On 3/28/21, the patient received Pfizer (Lot ER8730 in the left deltoid).  Following her 15 minute observation period, she rose from her chair and fell to the ground unconscious.  She was taken to the treatment tent and observed to have 'seizure like jerking of upper and lower extremities, fluttering eyelids, unarousable.'  Vitals stable (BP=103/68, HR =111, SpO2=98%).  Patient and family described this seizure as similar to the ones she experiences due to stress/anxiety.  Symptoms resolved, no medication treatment needed.  She was advised to follow-up with PCP regarding 2nd dose, and if proceeds, recommended to lie down in treatment tent for 2nd dose (which was then done on 2nd dose).  Patient reported that she has not had seizures with other vaccine administrations.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My dad had his first Moderna shot on 3/2/21; second shot was on 3/30/21.  On 3/3/21, he woke up and got Bell's Palsy. After doing some serious research, I discovered that Bell's Palsy is a side affect and per VAERS,, there's over 400 cases.  My dad's right side of his face was getting worse to wear he couldn't close his right eye and as of today, 4/23/21, he still can't close it and my mom has to continue to put eye drops in his eye so his eye doesn't dry and damage his cornea.  My dad goes see's his eye dr every two (2) weeks. One time the eye dr told my mom that my dad's face was getting better when it was obvious that it was getting worse.  My dad has Dimentia and from this reaction to his first shot, the dimentia has gotten worse; going downhill really fast and this is coming from my mom who is with him 24/7.  Prior to getting the second shot on 3/30/21, all the doctors were telling my mom that it's fine for my dad to get the second shot.  I told my mom that I didn't have a good feeling about my dad getting the second shot since most of the common side effects come with the second and if my dad is like this from the first shot, I can't imagine what would happen from getting the second shot. My dad said that he didn't want the second shot and all that he wants is eye to get better and to this day, that's all he wants and we keep on telling my dad that it'll eventually go away but we don't know when.  Studies need to be done on who the vaccine reacts to those with dimentia.  Not enough studies on why people get Bell's Palsy and other major side effects from the vaccine.

4/5/2021--Received Janssen vaccine.  Felt very hot during the day.   4/6/2021--Woke up with very bad headache and rash on the injected arm plus on my stomach.  Went for a walk and felt pain in my left calf and achilles tendon.  Went to work.  4/7/2021--Started my work day as a Personal Trainer/Fitness Instructor at 6am as usual.  Taught cycling classes and trained a few clients.  Went for walk.  Still had a headache.  When I got in my car to head home, my vision was super blurry and I felt very dizzy.  I ate an orange and peanuts and hydrated more.  I was not even sure I could drive home.  I got home told my family how I was feeling.  My husband noticed my eyes were very red and swollen.  I took a shower, drank a smoothie and ate a salad.  Used my aunt's BP cuff to check my BP and it was 148/99.  I have NEVER had HBP.    4/8/21--Woke up feeling disoriented as if the left side of my face, body were off--neurological stuff.  I went to reach for grapes in the refrigerator and could not grab them.  I felt like I have never felt before and ask my husband to drive me to the ER.  While at the waiting room at the ER, I felt chest tightness and pain and nauseous.  My BP was 153/111.  Again, I have never been diagnosed or been treated for hypertension.  They did EKG, lab tests, chest X-ray.  Once my BP came down, they sent me home.   This is before all the JJ Janssen vaccine "news" came out and the reasons it was paused.  I developed a very bad cough about two hours after I got home from the ER.  4/9/11--Made appointment with a brand new primary care doctor.  Saw her on Monday 4/12/2021 as recommended by ER.  I had never met her before.  She prescribed a very low dose of BP medication, which I did not take because the number one side-effect is dry-cough.  I was already coughing a lot, later on with blood.  4/11/2021--Still feeling pretty bad, I woke up to the news of the Janssen vaccine being paused.  Frankly, I felt relieved that I was not going crazy.  This truly has been one of the hardest things I have ever gone (and still am) going through.  I became concerned about the pain in the left calf and heel could be a clot.   Called primary care doctor.  Had ultrasound of legs and chest x-ray the following day   4/12/2021--Had persistent cough with blood.  Went to ER at 9pm.  Had EKG, blood work, CT without contrast of chest, covid test--negative.  Got home around 2am.  4/19/21--Followed up with primary care doctor who after explaining to her I am extremely fatigued, still blurry vision, dizzy, cough better but not gone, chest discomfort on the left side, she referred me to an ophtamologist and cardiologist.  My insurance and this poorly established referral system is very difficult to navigate.  Up to now I am still waiting for the referral and pre-aurhtorization to the opthtamologist.  (4/23/2021).  I want to say, I am pretty healthy. I have worked in fitness and wellness for over 30 years. I have never drank alcohol, smoked or done any drugs.  Prior to this no physician has told me I have HBP or any issues for which I have to be medicated.  I take zero medications.  Even when I had the bad headache from the vaccine I took nothing.  I have not worked in two weeks and had not driven until last saturday.  If I don't work, I don't get paid.   I pay for almost $600/month for my insurance in the marketplace.  This has been another stressor of this storm.  Getting providers to really listen and insurance companies to take situations like this seriously.   I could not drive at night.  This has been rough and I look forward to being myself soon.  This reaction felt like a heart attack/stroke with extreme fatigue, acid reflux, cough with some blood, muscular pain.  The rash and headaches were the least of my concerns.  I am not yet recovered from all of this.  I sure hope there is no permanent damage and that this too shall pass.  It is important to note that I have tried reporting this event several times to the VAERS website online.  I completed the 4-5 pages multiple times and it would not let me submit.  I also called the VAERS 1-800 number to report and they told me to go back to the online form.  I left several messages when I could not get it done online and to this date no one has called me back.  I called to report my adverse reaction and they told me they do not take that info.  I also called the health dept.  After several phone calls to them a nurse called me back but did not take a formal report.  When someone is feeling pretty sick, this is a lot to ask of.  I persisted because I feel this is important to be reported.
LAB_DATA: Two ER visits--4/8/2021    4/14/21 Three primary care doctor visits Ultrasound of legs and chest x-rays Chest CT without contrast as contrast may aggravate reaction more EKGS, bloodwork One covid test--negative
ALLERGIES: None up to the Janssen vaccine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After my first shot I had a swollen arm at the injection site, and extreme fatigue. Arm Soreness happened 3-4 hours after injection  My SECOND SHOT is where I had the Severe reaction: I decided to treat at home because I had my tens units, leg massager, and pain relievers.  Symptoms: extreme fatigue, sore muscles (aching) and some hardness at injection site, muscle weakness, joint pain, diarrhea, dizziness, fever, one case of the sweats (due to fever), headache, increased heart beat, sore throat (from dripping nose and yet it was also stopped up making the headache happen), and (some short breathing-but I have an inhaler for that, so I was fine).   I began feeling them in the evening about 8-9 hours after the shot. I didn?t sleep well that night, and spent most of it in pure agony and searing pain. I have fibromyalgia and the shot clearly aggravated that condition so I felt like my veins were on fire. -and still do.  Third day after symptoms have lessened, but still persist. Doing all I can to rest and get better.   HOW I TREATED: -Took Tylenol -Took an episome salt bath ?? first. Soaped and rinsed after. -Used a Cain or a family member help me walk to and from the bathroom so I didn?t fall over due to dizziness.  -Called my Dr. And asked for a limited dose of Tramadol-pain meds (I?m allergic to narcotics and opiate pain treatments) -I used 2 at home tens units and had them all over my body. (That I got originally for my back pain and fibromyalgia) -I used my top of the line leg massager (that I got originally for my fibromyalgia)  -My family made chicken soup -I drank water, Pedialite with juice, and mint tea. -Took my temperature regularly to keep up with Tylenol -Eventually used over the counter lidocaine and Aspercream all over my body. -Had a pressure cuff at home to monitor vitals

Covid-19 vaccine JJ: 32 y.o. male w/ no PMH presenting 2 weeks after receiving his Johnson & Johnson COVID vaccine after having severe L calf pain found to have thrombocytopenia.    From H&P on 4/21, Patient reports that he had both fevers and aches after his vaccine (4/8/2021). Several days later developed low back pain radiating into his left leg which he initially attributed to sciatica. However, several days later, he went for a 6 mile hike, and felt that his left leg was hurting more. He went to PCP, where he received a blood test and was found to have a platelet count in the low 60s. This was initially thought to be a lab error, but he noticed that his left leg was swollen, somewhat red, and appeared that his blood vessels were swollen. This swelling resolves when he is lying down, and is worsened when he is standing. He received an US to r/o DVT, which was negative. However, after his repeat platelet count demonstrated thrombocytopenia, he was sent to the ED. He denies any recent leg trauma, though he has broken his leg before nearly 15 years ago.  He denies weakness or issues going to the bathroom. Denies chest pain or shortness of breath. Denies chills, fevers, but did wake up last 2 nights drenched in sweat. He also reports a petechial rash on his legs.   As of 4/22, medical team suspects Vaccine-induced thrombocytopenic purpura (VITT). VITT requires 1) thrombocytopenia, 2) documented clot, 3) positive PF4 Ab, and 4) recent AstraZeneca or J&J vaccine. He meets criteria 1, 3, and 4. He has clinical signs of DVT but does not have a documented clot. Patient has L calf tenderness and prominent pooling of blood and vein engorgement of the L leg when he stands up. Possible that he had a DVT or multiple that cleared and now he has post-thrombotic syndrome. This is consistent with the pooling of blood with gravity and relief of symptoms with elevation. As he has had 2 negative US for DVT, unlikely that he has an unresolved DVT. abdominal and head CT are neg for thrombosis.
LAB_DATA: Plt=46  on 4/21 at ED. PF4 = 2.79 on 4/22 d-dimers >14,000 on 4/22 Hemoglobin=13.5 4/22Treated as follows: - s/p IVIG x2 doses, 1 g/kg per day. 4/21-4/22 - s/p cryo 10 units 4/22 - prednisone 1 mg/kg/day - IV argatroban  Heparin antibody immunology pending

Patient stays an additional 10-15 minutes and exits in wheelchair as patient "wants to take it easy" and it is a long walk back to car. Patient stable upon dismissal from observation. I decided to stop outside a doctor?s office in the Center and take some Benadryl. After a few minutes I felt a little better , and drove 3 minutes to my  own doctor?s office. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt was given Moderna for the 1st dose of Covid vaccine.  Pt came in for the 2nd dose during a Vaccination clinic that was for Pfizer patients only.  It was given by another nurse, before I got to his paperwork.  When I discovered he had the Moderna vaccine for the first dose and was given Pfizer vaccine for the 2nd dose.  Pt was notified of the error.  Pt was followed up with by his primary provider NP.  Pt did not have any adverse reactions due to receiving different vaccines.  The follow up research indicated that not to give another dose of Moderna.  The Administrator for the clinic was notified of the medication error.  Provider was already notified by the patient and it was discussed in the medical staff meeting the next Monday.  Subsequently, the patient was not harmed.  We now double check every patient coming through the door of which vaccine they received first during a vaccination clinic. RN

On the night of my J&J my vaccine , I felt very tired and sleepy but I could not sleep. The next morning I felt a burning sensation to my eyes as well to my right ear and that went away. I went to see my PCP that day as well because I was having a pressure sensation down my right calf and leg. On Wednesday I felt numbness sensation down my right arm and the right side of my body was weak. On Thursday, I called my PCP who advised me to go to the ER and to get monitored for thrombosis. I also began to have headaches and blurry vision. At the ER they performed an ultrasound and did lab work. The ultrasound exam did not show evidence of thrombosis or blood clots. The ER physicians told me to rest and elevate my legs. I also noticed that  my BP was 130/90 which I never had before. To this day I still have throbbing sensation to my right calf and leg.  I again went to the ER and thy monitored me. They told me to take Ibuprofen for pain and again did an ultrasound which did not show any blood clots. I then started to have a burning sensation to my skull and scalp and also my left arm. I have not fully recovered from my symptoms.
LAB_DATA: Ultrasound of my right leg, lab work

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On April 13th, patient noted a black spot in her vision with her right eye. As the day progressed, she began experiencing a headache which worsened in severity despite treating with medication. She started treating with Tramadol; when that didn't help, she took her prescription oxycodone (5mg/325mg) 3 hours later, q6 hours x 2. That evening, patient experienced 1 episode of emesis and thought she may not be feeling well, so went to bed. When she woke the next morning, she felt better, but still noted the black spot in her vision. She sought care with her Ophthalmologist, who evaluated her, and he did not believe it was related to her vision.  He referred her for an MRI, immediately. MRI revealed a stroke in the occipital region. She was admitted and given IV fluid along with another panel of testing. She was seen by Neurologist and Hospitalist; more testing was completed on Friday, including bloodwork which revealed high potassium levels which was treated. She was also given 1 unit of blood. She discharged on Friday and was started on Clopidogrel (75 mg). Follow up appointments are scheduled with eye doctor, neurology, internist.  Right eye was affected and vision will not likely return, per her doctors.
LAB_DATA: MRI on 4/15/21 which revealed stroke in occipital region Blood work on 4/16/21 and 4/17/21, revealed high potassium and low Hgb which were both treated.
OTHER_MEDS: Multivitamin Acetaminophen PRN Allopurinol (100 mg) Alprazolam (0.5 mg) Calcitrilo (0.25 mg 3 times/week) Tums, TID cyanocobalamin, B12 shot q21 days Levothyroxine (50 mg) Magnesium Oxide (400 mg) Metoprolol (50 mg, daily) Sodium Bicarb 650
CUR_ILL: None reported, to the best of her knowledge

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt sitting for her 15 minute post vaccine period. At end of 15 minutes she was noted to become less responsive and slump in her chair. Speech not clear, could not keep eyes open. Appeared pale and clammy. Lightly retching but did not vomit. With 2 assist were able to get patient to wheechair and then to gurney nearby. BP immediately taken - it was ~ 165/80.  Pulse = 70. Pulse ox = 94%. Her color remained somewhat pale.  Pt able to talk more clear and state she is a diabetic and requests glucose check. We called a "first responder". Glucose machine arrived and her glucose was noted to be 287. She notes it has been "very up and down lately" and recently made changes in her insulin/med regimen. She states she did eat breakfast and took both her long and short acting insulin. She did eat a cracker and then after ~ 20 minutes wanted to sit up. She sat up and appeared improved but not 100%. Her BP sitting up was ~ 125/70. Pulse remained 70. She then stood up to get into wheelchair but once in wheelchair began to become less responsive again and appeared more pale. She was then put back on gurney with assist of 3 and taken to ER.  Per ER note, she did have some vomiting and dizziness. Her BP was initially 222/99. BP improved to 1178/84. She was given meclizine and rested. She felt improved and able to ambulate, and was dc'd from ER.
LAB_DATA: In ER pt underwent CT of head, CXR, and EKG - all unremarkable.  CBC and CMP done - only abnormal is K = 3.5 and WBC = 10.8.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I myself a healthy physician with no prior medical illnesses received  Pfizer COVID19 vaccine first on 12/18/20 and second dose on 1/8/21 both doses at Hospital , ( they have the information of the lots)- Then on March 19th I started to develop an acute ascending sensory symptoms first in feet and then arms ; also involved torso . Sensory symptoms consisted of pins and needles and paresthesias . They persists on even today but less intense . Also had temperature dysregulation of the feet when shoes worn. There seem to have also some changes in my sweat gland activity. Saw my PCP and neurologist with working diagnosis of acute sensory neuropathy of unclear etiology. Though this could be idiopathic but  like to check out if any association with  COVID19 vaccine as this only association i could think about in healthy patient ie myself with no medial issues or any acute illness recently nor any systemic disorders to account for symptoms ; wanted to report so that you are aware and I personally wanted to see if this is being recognized in other vaccine recipients  and might help me to arrive at a diagnosis.
LAB_DATA: All pertaining blood work for systemic causes of neuropathy on 3/24/21 which were neg except for slightly low Vit D which is being supplemented . EMG 3/31/21 was normal.  Clinical suspicion of acute sensory neuropathy based on clinical symptoms . Don't have yet confirmatory skin biopsy to look into small fiber neuropathy.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: History of chronic migraine, completely stable at the time of vaccination (no migraine x 3 months). Severe migraine started a few days after the first dose of the Moderna vaccine. This migraine was different in severity and quality than my typical migraines. It was VERY severe (average 8/10) and didn't subside for six weeks (daily, severe, intractable migraine), at which time I was two weeks post second dose. At that time,  it started to subside and respond to treatment and about three weeks after the second dose it went away completely. I was seen my neurologist's office and the emergency room multiple times for migraine infusions and developed Cushing's syndrome as a result of the multiple high doses of steroids I required to treat the migraine. My primary care doctor attributed this 6-week string of very severe migraines to the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Date of office visit: 4/22/2021 2:15 PM  Intake done by: LPN Reason for today's visit: New Patient 30 minutes HR: 80, regular rate & rhythm   BP: 136/78 (prehypertension)    weight: 195 lbs  88.6 kg    temperature: 98.5 F height: 5 ft 6 inch (measured) body mass index: 31.5 Obesity Classification: Class I, Simple obesity   Progress Note xxxxx 4/22/2021  Patient is a 43-year-old female referred to me for management of hemorrhage into her pituitary gland.  February 9, 2021  11 AM she received Moderna vaccine. by 7 PM she had a severe headache, leg numbness, severe arthralgias in her knees, global paresthesias, pressure behind her eyes, she describes her head is very heavy and pressurized was very painful.   Symptoms lasted for three days and gradually remitted. To a lesser degree  the headache persisted longer but resolved  March 10, 2021  received Moderna vaccine. On same day she developed headache, chest pain, back pain, leg numbness. She states that when she walked it exacerbated chest pain and headache and she had to walk very gently on her toes. She tried Tylenol, ibuprofen without effect. The symptoms persisted. She started taking two aspirin a day.  March 14 she worked third shift as usual (despite symptoms)  March 15, the symptoms were bad enough that she felt she had to go to the emergency room.  March 15, 2021 18:56      CT Head or Brain C-:    7 mm rounded hyperdensity within the pituitary gland which may represent a hyperdense pituitary mass lesion.    Associated hemorrhage is not excluded.   March 15, 2021 22:34   MRI Brain C-/C+:    There is 0.6 x 0.6 x 0.7 cm round structure in the anterior pituitary gland with high T1 signal, dark T2 signal, susceptibility artifact and no enhancement.    This likely represents a hemorrhage within the microadenoma.    Advise neurosurgical consult and follow-up MRI in 6 months. ________________  3/17/2021 I was consulted (while she was in hospital, chart review only. Patient not seen at that time)   I wrote...  PITUITARY ACTH Patient had ACTH stimulation test yesterday. Assuming she has received no steroid Rx during this admission prior to the ACTH stimulation test (as I have been told), then these results confirm that her adrenal gland has the ability to respond to ACTH and thus there is no reason to believe the underlying pituitary abnormality had resulted in chronic ACTH deficiency from the pituitary lesion that resulted in hemorrhage.  3/16/2021 4:32 PM   .Cort 30 min Stim   Cortisol 30 Minutes Post ACTH      19.3         mcg/dL   Cortisol 60 Min                    27.6         mcg/dL            As the pituitary hemorrhage was an acute event, it is possible the pituitary currently does not have the ability to make adequate amounts of ACTH, despite the normal ACTH stim test, but the situation is too acute to cause the adrenal to atrophy (as a result of chronic ACTH deficiency) and she still could have secondary adrenal insufficiency. When there is a chronic ACTH deficiency of sufficient duration, the adrenal gland will eventually atrophy and the patient will then develop primary adrenal insufficiency as well and then the ACTH stim test will become abnormal.  As we do not know if her pituitary can make ACTH appropriately, I think it would be prudent to treat the patient with PREDNISONE 2.5 mg qAM for now even thought we do not know for certain whether her pituitary can make ACTH. After discharge, she should be evaluated by endocrine to assess for ACTH deficiency. She should be advised to seek medical attention if she develops symptoms of adrenal insufficiency like nausea, emesis, abd pain, orthostatic symptoms.   PITUITARY TSH 3/15/2021 11:47 PM   T3 Total                      83         (normal: 60-181)  nGm/dL   T4, Total                     7.3        (normal: 4.5-13.3)  mcg/dL   TSH, 3rd gen                  2.160      (normal: 0.358-3.740)  mclU/ml  I think, based on above admission TFTs, she should also be treated with LEVOTHYROXINE 100 mcg qAM even though we do not know for certain if she has central hypothyroidism. This too should be reassessed in the future.   PITUITARY LH/FSH If she acutely or recently developed secondary amenorrhea and FSH is not c/w menopause, then that would suggest the lesion or hemorrhage has causes hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism. This situation would increase the probability she has central adrenal insufficiency and central hypothyroidism. If menses remains normal henceforth, the it is more likely her ability to make TSH and ACTH are normal.  _______________   Patient was discharged on levothyroxine 100 �g in the morning and prednisone 2.5 mg daily. She's also on iron pills.  Past medical history: Iron deficiency anemia. Treatment was an IUD, after which she's gained a lot of weight.  Medicines: IUD, Levothyroxine 100 mcg QAM, prednisone 2.5 mg QAM, ferrous sulfate 325 mg daily  Allergies: none  No cigarette use, alcohol abuse or drug use  Family social history: patient has three children. High school educated. Healthcare worker.  REVIEW OF SYSTEMS: overall health is good. She feels well. No headache.  No nausea. No nocturia  Physical exam:  Extraocular muscles intact.  VF full Lungs are clear.  Cardiac exam regular.  Impression: hemorrhage into pituitary gland  Temporarily, symptoms correlate with covid vaccination in a women who previously was (reportedly) dx with covid infection. Maybe the pituitary hemorrhage was the result of the coronavirus vaccination or the aspirin she was taking.   At this point she's feeling well. It's been about one month since the event. I'd like to wait another month and then proceed with testing of a pituitary gland to try to figure out if she really needs to remain on levothyroxine and prednisone and reimage the pituitary.  On the day of the testing she will take neither medicine in the morning. Will then measure LH, FSH, estradiol, TSH free T4 and cortisol and renal panel. Patient will then receive ACTH 0.25 mg IM and have cortisol measured at 30 minutes and 60 minutes. I will follow-up with her by phone.  She scheduled to see Dr. April 26. I would like to do another MRI but I would prefer to wait another month as she is clinically doing well and I want to allow the pituitary more time to "heal"/stabilize.  No follow-up is scheduled with me, if Dr. does not order an MRI and I will after I received next blood test.  M.D. 4/22/2021 3:40 PM Electronically signed by:  M.D. on 4/23/2021 2:47 PM

In the computer system that we use for patients, if the syringe next to the patient's name is a green color, that means the patient is cleared for vaccination. If it is red, I carefully review the questionnaire with the patient. Patient told me before the vaccination that she doesn't do well with vaccines. I vaccinated her. She said the vaccine hurt her and the first vaccine did not hurt her. She needed to sit on her chair where she was vaccinated for a little while after. She turned yellow, was snoring and fell off the chair. I turned her to her side and called for help. We fanned her and she was given water. She put her head down on the chair while sitting on the floor and she asked for a trash can and she threw up. She also told me that she felt disoriented after waking up. She has a previous history of this reaction to vaccines(but with no vomiting)..also I don't think she experienced these reactions to vaccines the past few years. She never vomited after a vaccine. She also said she had no problem with the first Pfizer vaccine. We brought a nurse to assist her. I checked on her after 15 minutes and she was cold and sweaty. I seated her for an additional 15 minutes. I asked her if she wanted me to call 911. I also advised her that if she still did not feel well after she left the pharmacy, that she can go to the Emergency Room. Her husband was with her.
PRIOR_VAX: She does experience these reactions to vaccines without vomiting. But no reaction the past few years?

Patient was given her first dose of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine. Patient had stated that she had felt lightheaded when she was given 4 vaccines at one time in the past. We advised patient to remain seated for 15 minutes for monitoring. Patient felt more comfortable standing next to her seated sister, who had also received the vaccine. The sister said the patient had told her she started feeling lightheaded and walked over to sit down on the other chair. Once seated, per the sister, the patient slumped to the floor and started shaking. At this point, we were alerted, but after a few seconds, the shaking had stopped and the patient was fully alert. The patient was unaware of what had happened. We called 911 and paramedics came to assess the patient. The patient remained seated on the ground until paramedics arrived. The paramedics assessed her vitals and everything was normal. The paramedics were comfortable with the patient going home with her sister, but upon standing up, the patient felt lightheaded again. At this point, the paramedics thought it would be best for the patient to be monitored at the hospital. The patient agreed to be taken to for further monitoring.
LAB_DATA: Paramedics determined that all vitals were normal when assessed 15 minutes after event.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 2 1/2 days after receiving my first vaccine dose (on 03/27/2021), I started to experience a very painful adverse event on the taste buds on my tongue. Certain taste buds on my tongue were so sensitive that it hurt to touch them to my teeth or the top of my mouth. It was difficult to eat, and I moved to a liquid diet for a few days.  After much research, it was clear that I was experiencing transient lingual papillitis (lie bumps) that persisted for about 7 days then disappeared. At the time, I wasn't sure if it was related to the Pfizer vaccine or not.  When I received my second dose on 04/18/2021, the adverse event happened again after 2 1/2 days. It was then clear to me that this issue was directly related to the Pfizer vaccine.

That evening at approximately 6:00pm, she had a red rash on her upper chest and throat. She stated that she was having a hard time breathing and swallowing. I gave her  a Benadryl tablet and watched her for approximately 15-20 minutes. she continued to feel tightness in her throat and said it burned when she swallowed. She confirmed again that she felt her throat was swelling. I drove her to the closest ER located at. My daughter was seen and it was determined that she was having an allergic reaction. DR recommended continue Benadryl tab every 4 hours for the next 12-24- hours. We were discharged to home. I administered another does of Benadryl at approximately 10:15pm. My daughter went to sleep. I woke her up at 3:00am to check on her and she stated she did not have a rash and her throat was fine. She was running a low grade fever of 100.5. I gave her 500 mg of Tylenol for the fever. When my daughter woke later that morning at approximately 8:30am, she still did not have a rash or throat swelling. Her fever was gone.

Called to evaluate patient in COVID-19 vaccination clinic area after witnessed "fainting" at ~12:30 PM.  Briefly this is a 23 yo female with unremarkable PMHx; Meds- OCPs; Allergies- PCN and Gluten. Pt received the first dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine at 12:25 PM with RN. Per RN report the patient informed her that she had a remote history of "passing out" after a vaccine as a child, but it had not happened recently.  The RN observed the patient at her vaccine station for 3 min then accompanied her to the observation area.  Per report of COVID-19 Patient Observer, pt was seen falling out of her chair in a seated position and it was unclear if she hit her head.  Per a witness, pt hit her head on the computer cart that was nearby.  The COVID-19 Patient Observer called for assistance and 911 was called.  She was immediately evaluated by COVID-19 Patient observer and RN and noted to be unresponsive initially.  The RN reported that she opened her eyes and became verbally responsive to verbal stimuli and touch.  Upon my arrival, pt was noted to be responsive and lying on floor on her abdomen.  She initially denied pain, but later complained of pain at crown of her head to touch.  Pt denied CP, HA, SOB, difficulty breathing, pruritis, rash, nausea, or visual disturbances.  Orthostatics were obtained (lying- 124/90-102; sitting- 137/81-115; Standing 123/87 - 96).  Patient maintained her O2 sat at 98% throughout the evaluation.  She was assisted to wheelchair and reported feeling better.   PE: A&O x 3 HEENT: Normocephalic, tenderness to palpation at crown of head, no lacerations or bruising noted, pupils equal CV: Tachycardic, regular rhythm, no M/R/G Resp: CTA B no W/R Ext: No UE or LE pain to palpation or edema noted  A/P: 23 yo s/p COVID-19 vaccine with likely vasovagal reaction and head trauma.    1. Vasovagal Reaction/Head Trauma - Pt transported by EMS to local hospital for evaluation  - Telemedicine visit with COVID-19 vaccine clinic on Monday 4/26/2021  2. COVID-19 Vaccine - VAERS report to be filled by Dr.  - FU for COVID-19 vaccine in 4 weeks  - Pt to receive vaccine in supine position and be observed for min 30 min - Recommend pt to be accompanied by friend/family member at next visit

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On the day after the injection, a boil appeared on my elbow.  The boil was like a blister without any pain, no redness, nothing.  Just like a big (20 cc) ball of lymph (I suppose it is lymph). I am a long-term survivor of COVID19.  I believe (have no proof) that I got it last January at the Chinese New Year Party.  I felt sick some 10 or 15 days later.  At the time, I thought that my vertebrae have unfused and barely could move.  Little by little improved, but then lymph accumulated in my body. The lymph would go into the muscles and make every move to be painful. My health degenerated until July 31st. I gained weight. At the time, doctors knew nothing and my self-diagnosis was that I could have blood clots. On July 31st, I changed the diagnosis for generalized inflammation.  I treated the generalized inflammation with exercise considering that the inflation was proportional to the fat in my body.  It worked. I am now 21 lbs lighter and better. That is when I received this new vaccine.  The boil is not unexpected, considering the history.
LAB_DATA: No medical test or lab results were done.  I called Moderna to inform them about these symptoms.  They didn't care and claimed they didn't do any medical or laboratory tests.  It would be worthwhile to drain my boils and see what kind of antibody I came up with.  My boil might save Mankind..:)

Patient received her dose around 5:10pm.  She did not report any anaphylaxis or allergies prior to vaccination.  She was monitored for 15 minutes and then left the facility.  She had driven about 5-7 miles and then started to feel as if her throat was tightening/closing in.  She stated that she could not swallow her saliva.  She stated that her tongue felt tingly.   She turned around in the car and returned to the facility.  She arrived around1745.  She was able to talk freely, although she stated that her voice was lower than normal.  She did not exhibit any facial or neck swelling and did not have any rash to her trunk or to her injection site.  She denied itching.  Initial vital signs: BP 124/74, p-79, SaO2 99%.  She stated that she was sensitive to Diphenhydramine and could not take that medication.  During the next 5-10 minutes, her symptoms did not progress.  She then revealed her history of CRPS/reflex sympathetic dystrophy.  She stated that she had sensitivities to many medications, and that she just doesn't know until she tries one.  She denies ever having anaphylaxis but states that she thinks she has come close to it a few times, but "rides it out".  She also stated a history of asthma, and that how she was feeling was similar to how she feels after an asthma attack.  Asked her if she had a rescue inhaler with her, but she stated that she did not.  She was further observed, and at 1810 the left side of her throat was improving but the right side was still tight.  Five minutes later, she stated that she was then able to swallow.  By 1820, she stated that everything was improved.  She felt well enough to return home.  Another set of VS were taken:  BP 110/60, P-68, SaO2 99%.  She was instructed to let her husband drive her home and to follow up with her PCP regarding this episode and follow-up.  She was additionally instructed that if her symptoms worsened, that she was to call 911.  Also talked to her husband and instructed him regarding worsening of symptoms and follow-up.  Called client today 4/23/21 at 11:30 and she reports that she did have a similar episode of the sensation like her throat was closing yesterday 4/22/21, but it resolved on its own without intervention.  She also reported nausea and lightheadedness s/p vaccination.  She states that she is feeling fine today.
CUR_ILL: Reports history of asthma and reflex sympathetic dystrophy, or complex regional pain syndrome.
ALLERGIES: She didn't report any allergies prior to vaccination.  Afterwards, she reported allergy to seafood and stated that she has had sensitivities to many things, but has never had anaphylaxis.

J&J COVID Vaccine EUA  J&J Vaccine 4/10/2021  4/13/21: Believes she is having a reaction to her Johnson and Johnson COVID-19 vaccination.  This vaccination was given on 04/10/2021. Patient is 39-year-old female with a past medical history significant for ulcerative colitis that has been in remission since the patient was 21 years of age, epileptic seizures on Vimpat and clonazepam. Patient comes in as a transfer with a chief complaint of possible reaction to Johnson and Johnson COVID-19 vaccine.  Patient presents with multiple complaints.  The patient states that upon receiving the vaccine on 04/10/2021 she suddenly developed presyncopal episodes where she felt like she was about to pass out but that subsided later on.  12 hours following the shot she had intense headache which was frontal and then later on travel to the back of her head and traveled down her spine. Patient described the headache to be the worse headache of her life, stated that it was worse than going through labor.  Patient stated that she received morphine which helped her with the headache. Patient also complained of chest pain which was left-sided with no radiation, constant.  No history of previous myocardial infarctions. Her troponins that were conducted were negative. Patient also complained of experiencing blood in her stool. She stated that when she wiped herself on the morning of 04/13/2021 she experience blood on the toilet paper and blood in the bowel.  However, her stool occult blood that was conducted was negative. Patient is being followed by Neurology, she contacted her neurologist and they recommended to come to the ED with concerns of thromboembolism.  Patient's D-dimer was negative. Patient denied any recent travel anywhere or coming into contact with anyone sick. She denied developing any fevers cough shortness of breath abdominal pain nausea vomiting or any urinary concerns.  4/15/21: Patient is a 39-year-old female with a past medical history significant for ulcerative colitis that has been in remission since the patient was 21 years of age, epileptic seizures on Vimpat and clonazepam. Patient comes in as a transfer with a chief complaint of possible reaction to Johnson and Johnson COVID-19 vaccine.  Headache:  MRI brain and MRI venogram was ordered.  MRI brain did show concerning signed for idiopathic intracranial hypertension.  Neurology was consulted.  Patient had high volume LP.  Patient responded well post LP.  Patient will be discharged on topiramate with a taper instructions per neurology.  Patient will make appointment with Ophthalmology.  Patient will follow up with Neurology as well. Chest pain concerning for ACS: Negative troponin.  EKG normal sinus rhythm. Concern for vaccine reaction:  Patient has J&J vaccine.  No clots were noted. Patient's symptoms are most likely are secondary to idiopathic intracranial hypertension and history of migraines.  4/16/2021: 39-year-old female presents emergency room with chief complaint of headache.  Onset this morning. Headache is generalized. Headache is constant.  Headache is worth with position change. Such as moving head side to side or with changing from lying to sitting and sitting to standing.  Headache improves with lying supine.  To has tried pushing fluids, taking over-the-counter medication, and also increasing her caffeine intake to offset the headache.  She denies any of these helping with her symptoms. Patient's pain is right an 8 out of 10. The patient denies anything additional alleviating and or aggravating factors to chief complaint.  Today when the patient's headache started.  She contacted her neurologist. She was told to come to the emergency department for a blood patch.  The patient added that her neurologist felt that she needs a blood patch not only because of the recent lumbar puncture but because there was at minimum 25 mL of spinal fluid removed at the time of her lumbar puncture. This lumbar puncture occurred under fluoroscopy.  However, they had difficulty getting the pressure gauge on thus, more than 25 mL was removed..  Pain Pain Scale:   8 /10. Timing: constant.  gradual. The day after receiving my first vaccine, I began to develop a headache and fatigued. I was unable to move my left arm much higher than an inch or two. My arm pain got better after 24 hours, but the headache and fatigue persisted. I felt well enough to work on April 12, 13 and 14 and went outside my home on the 12, 14 and 15, interacting with other people while masked. On April 16, the extreme fatigue set in. I could not get out of bed. EXTREME. That entire weekend I stayed in bed with the chills and also developed nasal congestion that has persisted to the time of this writing (April 23). On April 19, I started spotting and started my period (old blood) two weeks early. That has for the most part subsided to the level of my usual discharge, though it is a bit heavier than normal.  Also on April 19, the sore throat and chest pain started. I went for a COVID test today. Negative result. Chest pain is similar in location and scope to when I suffered with pericarditis years ago.  Took a sick day off of work. Fatigue getting better, but very very wiped out by the end of the day. Brain is foggy.  April 20 - virtual visit with my primary doctor to discuss symptoms. Chest pain continually getting worse, harder to take a deep breath, like when the doctor asks to "take a deep breath and hold it," that really hurts. Can breathe regularly fine. But just sitting on the couch I'm in pain. Laying down hurts the most. Get bloodwork, chest x-ray and covid test done. All normal.   April 22 - Chest pain continues to get worse. Starting to cough. Go to Urgent Care  at request of primary care doctor. Another covid test done, xray taken, flu swab., EKG. All normal. They send me to emergency room at  Hospital additonal assessment. EKG, ultrasound of heart and lungs, bloodwork done, all normal. They send me home on ibuprofin and tell me to follow up with my cardiologist. They believe it to be presumptive pericarditis.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Monday, April 19, 2021, I had a Shingrix Vaccination about 3:30 p.m. at pharmacy.   The injection in my left shoulder did not hurt too much, but slowly the injection site turned painful, hot with swelling up to 6? long and about 4? wide.  (As of 4/23/21, it is still swollen and hot.)  I took my 3 mg Prednisone, Tylenol and went to bed because I had a low grade fever and a headache.  Tuesday morning, April 20, 2021, the pain started about 5 a.m. I had chills, a headache, and fever.  I stayed in bed; and I took Tylenol as directed, and as the day continued, I needed help to the toilet.  I tried to drink a lot of fluids and ate about 4 pieces of canned peaches.  I continued to get worse and my temperature rose to 103 degrees.  (My normal temperature is 97.4.)  At one point, I felt nauseous, and had dry heaves.    In hindsight, the first true indication there was anything really wrong was I could not get back in bed.  I also had very little balance and almost fell.  That may have been 10 or 11 p.m.  When I went to bed, I was out cold.  I think I was almost comatose and slept through wetting the bed.  Tuesday is a blur.  Wednesday, April 21, 2021 was a bad day.  I woke up at 5 am needing to use the toilet.  I got out of bed and collapsed and hit my had on the nightstand.  At that point, I could not move my legs to get up.  They were buckled under me, and my husband could not get me up, so he called 911.  I was taken by ambulance to hospital.  In the ER, my neurological issues were apparent.  I was able to give some information, though, much would not come to my mind.  I remembered I have Polymyalgia Rheumatica but did not remember for several hours that I had a maintenance chemo treatment for bladder cancer later this week, for which there is no evidence of disease. When asked to move an arm for any reason, I could not move them; the staff did.  When they let go, my arms just fell with gravity.  Sitting up without help was impossible. I said the only medicine I had taken was Tylenol and was very surprised to see I had actually taken my Prednisone the night before.  I was given 800 mg of Motrin, but I do not know how often.  I had some chills, fever and pain throughout my body most of the day.  I slept most of the time in the ER.  When I was brought lunch, I ate a few small squares of pears using a fork.  It was hard, I could not find my mouth with the fork.  The doctor said all of my many tests and vital signs were good.  When she asked me to lift my legs, I could not.  Thus, I was transferred to a bed in the hospital.  The only thing I ate there was a small bowl of applesauce again with difficulty.  I slept most of the time again.  My legs started to gain strength about 4 p.m., and I was released at 6:30 p.m.  I could have stayed the evening, but I wanted to go home.  Thursday, April 22, 2021 was a better day.  I started taking Bayer Back and Body Aspirin for my pain.  I was in less pain and more alert so I could isolate what hurt.  My left arm was still red, very hot and painful.  My right upper arm hurt too.  My headache was the worst, it even makes my ears hurt.  I got dressed and went outside for a half an hour.  I came in and put my pjs back on and went to bed.  I was still unsteady walking around. I had absolutely no energy and am unsteady while walking.   Friday, April 23, 2021.  I woke up hungry at six.  Ate two scrambled eggs, took a very fast shower because I could not stand very long, and went back to bed and slept for 5 hours.  I am still unsteady on my feet and only have a minor headache.  My arm is still hot to touch, but less swollen and painful.  I am still unsteady, but my mind is working a lot better.
LAB_DATA: April 21, 2019 I am not sure i f this is  all of the tests.  Blood work,  a Cat Scan of my head, a chest x-ray, and a COVID test
HISTORY: Polymyalgia Rheumatica  No evidence of disease bladder cancer, last chemo was March 26, 2021 Minor asthma
PRIOR_VAX: DPT 1991
ALLERGIES: Grasses, weeds, molds. My hospital records list other things that are no longer a problem,

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my second dose of Modena vaccine last Thursday (4/15) morning at 9am.  No initial reaction occurred.   Later that Thursday my arm got the expected tenderness, muscle ache. Towards evening, I got pretty tired and was starting to get some body aches, took 2 tylenol and went to bed at 9pm. Slept in late and was tired. Started to feel like mild flu which is what I expected.   Friday took some naps and continued mild flu symptoms. Went to bed about 8pm and got up at 5:00, feeling a bit better.   Saturday I continued to improve, arm was much better, less flu symptoms, didn't need tylenol, had turned the corner.  Cont'd... Saturday evening was going to go to bed at 10pm and noticed my left cheek was kind of pressing against my gums - it was swollen. It continued to swell some but was not hindering my throat or breathing.   I decided to stay awake, keep an eye on it and if necessary would go to an emergency room. The swelling increased only slightly more over the next couple of hours to the size of maybe a golf ball (a bit less) on the left side and a much smaller amount on the right side. No airway effects. I did apply some ice but not sure if that had an effect. I slept for a few hours.   Sunday morning I did not take my medications as a precaution.   Sunday the swelling was slightly less and seemed to be going down a bit. I took 2 Benedryl at 11:00 am which really knocked me out, slept. Sunday evening the swelling was noticeably improved but not gone. Took 1 Benedryl at 10:00pm bedtime.   Monday still had a bit of swelling on left and right swelling is nearly gone.  No other symptoms.

On the 3rd day after shot, swollen lymph node and jaw pain on the same side as injection. About 20 minutes after the vaccine, I felt like my throat was swelling, like an asthma attack. It was not severe. This lasted for about 2 hours. Less than 24 hours later, I started having chest pain when I would breathe.

Bruise-type pain at injection site starting +5 hours lasting for about a day. Mild Diarrhea starting +8 hours roughly every 1-2 hours for a day or so. Mild vertigo / balance issues starting +2 days lasting for 3-4 days. Can't confirm causation but definitely atypical / no other known cause. Difficulty maintaining balance (like walking while drunk only I don't drink anymore) NO nausea/spinning just balance.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Had the Moderna vaccine at 2pm on 4/21/2021.  The vaccine was perfect - no pain, no problem.  At 4pm I developed a fever over 101 degrees.  I took an advil and drank a lot of water.  About 3am on 4/22/2021 I awoke with severe pain in my arm, my shoulders, my neck and the muscles in the back of my head.  The pain was so severe that I couldn't raise my left (injection site) arm without significant pain.  I called out sick to work, took tylenol and put a heating pad on my arm, back & neck.  Later in the morning I noticed the skin on my neck and face (below my nose) was reddish and burning.  By mid-afternoon, my face below my nose began peeling and itching...like eczema - which I have.  By late afternoon, my neck - front and back began to peel as well.  It is now 4/23/2021.  The pain is better but still very sore.  The fever is down to about 100 degrees.  My face and neck still itch and are peeling, but not red anymore.  All in all, I'm thrilled to have received the vaccine and ready to live a more "normal" life.  I will take my second dose.  I thought you would might want to know how the vaccine affected someone with autoimmune diseases.
OTHER_MEDS: Multivitamin, Magnesium, Turmeric Capsule, Tart Cherry Juice
HISTORY: Fibromyalgia (20 years), Insomnia (20 years), Arthritis, IBS, Chronic Fatigue/Pain

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 5 minutes after injection, pt began complaining of "feeling warm." He was provided with water by a staff member. The patient then fell to the floor from a seated position in a chair in the observation area. The EMT and Paramedic immediately responded to the patient. They assessed the patient and brought him into a wheelchair once he was feeling well enough to do so. The patient never lost consciousness. Initial vitals: BP 96/60, O2 95% on room air, RR 24, HR 64. The Paramedic took a 12-lead EKG, result was Sinus rhythm with apparent ST elevation. Subsequent EKG was sinus brady with apparent ST elevation. The patient was free of contusions or scrapes from his fall from the chair. PT initially refused transportation to the emergency department. After some convincing, the patient was agreeable to seek elevated medical treatment and was transported by ambulance.
LAB_DATA: Pt refused blood glucose test. Two EKGs were accomplished as noted above.
CUR_ILL: Denied medical history. Denied alcohol and drug use.
HISTORY: Denied medical history. Denied alcohol and drug use.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: HPI: Patient is a * year old * who presents following administration of the first dose of the COVID19 vaccine in the left deltoid.  Patient has a history of vasovagal syncope/reaction and was not conscious upon medical response arrival.  No head trauma.  Patient denies allergies.  Patient denies past medical history.  Patient only taking a low dose combination OCP.  She states she has only eaten breakfast.  She otherwise denies chest pain, difficulty breathing, swelling of the face/lips/tongue/throat, skin rash/itching, cramping abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting.     Exam (update as needed): GEN: Patient not conscious upon arrival.  Upon reclining patient and elevating legs, patient alert & oriented x 4.  NAD HEAD: NCAT EYES: PERRL, EOMI upon intervention. ENT: Ears normal, Nose normal, OP normal, no evidence of angioedema NECK: Supple, without LAD.  CV: Weak, thready radial pulse.  RRR, no m/r/g PULM: Clear to auscultation bilaterally, no accessory muscle use ABD: Soft, no tenderness. SKIN: No rashes, skin warm and dry.  No erythema or edema of the injection site. MSK: FROM, MS 5/5 NEURO: Upon intervention, patient alert & oriented x 4.  CN 2-12 grossly intact, no ataxia, gait steady   Clinical Impression/Field Tx: Vasovagal syncope.  Upon reclining patient and elevating the legs, patient regained consciousness and was A&O x 4.  EMS called to the scene for further evaluation, to include EKG.  Patient not actively displaying signs or symptoms of anaphylaxis.  Vital signs stable upon transfer of care.   Instructed patient to consult their PCP regarding the post-vaccination reaction.  Patient instructed to go to emergency department should they develop chest pain, difficulty breathing, swelling of the face/lips/mouth/tongue/throat, or cramping abdominal pain with nausea/vomiting, as these are signs of possible anaphylaxis that requires immediate intervention.     Medications administered: None   Disposition:   EMS was called to the site for further evaluation.  Patient elected to not transport to the hospital and left with her parents.
PRIOR_VAX: Vasovagal syncope with all vaccines in the past

patient was treated with the Janssen/Johnson & Johnson COVID-19 adenovirus vaccine on Saturday April 10, 2021 and she relates having had symptomatic problems since that time stating prior to administration of the vaccine she was in her normal state of health.  She relates that on the evening of April 10 she had chills but otherwise no other major symptoms and the next day felt fine as well as during that week.  However she states that starting 1 week later on Saturday, April 17 she began feeling poorly characterized by a recurrence of hives that she has had in the past along with a sore throat.  She states this occurred while she was at work and describes the sore throat as unusual from prior sore throat she has had in the past with a description of a globus-like sensation along with some difficulties swallowing for more pressure than overt pain.  She attempted salt water gargles without benefit.  The rash was the characteristic hives rash that she has had on 2 prior occasions with rapid development of itchy red lesions scattered throughout especially in her proximal extremities and torso region.  She relates the hives worsened on Sunday, April 18 essentially from "head to toe" although not actually involving her face.  She also related new accompanying symptoms including diffuse arthralgias, stiffness and swollen painful muscles and joints.  This was throughout her entire body and somewhat of a migratory nature involving all of her major joints including the hands, wrists, shoulders, feet, ankles, knees and hips.  She states that because of the severity of symptoms she had an urgent care appointment on Sunday, April 18 and felt to have a exacerbation of urticaria for which she was prescribed montelukast, loratadine cimetidine and a Solu-Medrol Dosepak.  She states she was unable to fill the Solu-Medrol Dosepak initially but took the other medications without relief and then presented to the emergency room here at Hospital on Monday, April 19 where she had an evaluation which was largely unremarkable other than laboratory testing with a nonspecific elevation in inflammatory markers including a CRP of 5.7, ESR 34 and white blood count 15.92.  She was notably COVID-19 negative at that time as well as Monospot negative. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my second dose of Moderna?s Covid shot at 11:00am.  By approximately 11:00pm (or so) both my daughter and I who had the second doseh same lot, felt like we were dying.  The worst I have ever felt in my 48 years. 103� fever, such severe chills a heating pad and two VERY thick blankets didn?t help, every muscle hurt like I?d been hit by a car, my skin was so painful pajamas hurt, my hair hurt, my neck hurt, I had an excruciating headache (which is saying a lot as I?ve lived with chronic daily intractable migraine for 30 years and am sadly accustomed to severe pain) .  I took two of my Oxycodone I have for my migraines and they didn?t even touch the pain I was in.  Today, two days later, I have a 100� fever, sore throat, sore body but considerably less sore than that initial 12-14 hours of extreme pain, continued headache, still quite lethargic, injection site is extremely painful and skin all around is still very sore to touch.  Red and itchy and upper arm is swollen.    Knowing now how I/we (again, my almost 19yo had the exact same horrific symptoms) felt after the second dose, I would be very hard pressed to ever get this vaccination or any type of booster ever again.  It was that bad and I know the importance of this vaccine.

Patient received dose 1 of the COVID Moderna vaccine (lot 047B21A) at 1130. At 1200, patient reported to EMT that she felt nauseous, lightheaded, and pain radiating from the injection site in her right arm up to her shoulder. EMT alerted PHN who approached the patient to further assess. Vital signs: blood pressure 130/88, O2 96%, pulse 94, respirations 12. At 1207, patient reported the lightheaded had resolved and nausea was improving. Patient reported only eating a small breakfast. Allergies: epinephrine, Norco, Tramadol. Medical conditions include chronic migraines, status post gastric bypass surgery 2 weeks ago. Medications include: Effexor, Trazodone, Finasteride, Ubrelvy, ibuprofen, estradiol patch, diltiazem, progesterone, atorvastatin. At 1210, vital signs O2 95%, blood pressure 124/90, pulse 84, respirations 12. PHN offered Benadryl but patient declined. PHN encouraged patient to notify provider and when to contact 911. At 1217, vital signs: O2 93%, pulse 80, blood pressure 110/76, and respirations 14. Patient stood up, reported feeling dizzy with a headache. Patient sat back down and drank some water. AT 1220, patient stood up again reporting all her symptoms had resolved. Vital signs: blood pressure 138/74, O2 95%, respirations 14, pulse 82. PHN encouraged patient to stay until 1230 but patient insisted on leaving. Patient left walking with steady gait at 1221.
OTHER_MEDS: Effexor, Trazodone, Finasteride, Ubrelvy, ibuprofen, estradiol patch, diltiazem, progesterone, atorvastatin
HISTORY: chronic migraines, status post gastric bypass surgery 2 weeks ago

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Injection at 9:10am. Ten minutes after injection, severe swelling in left arm. Informed nurse. She stated to remove watch band that was cutting into left arm - the swelling was normal. Ten minutes after noticed arm swelling. Pressure on left and front of side of throat with difficulty breathing. Informed nurse. We talked and she suggested I get out of the car walk around and take deep breaths. After doing so I informed nurse my breathing wasn't any better. She took me inside one of the buildings and found someone to use a pulse ox to test blood oxygen level. She said it was fine and I was good to go when 30 minutes was up. Husband drove me home, I laid down for a nap at 2:30 pm and got up at 4:45 pm. I woke several times during nap due to pain in lower left arm and upper left chest. When I got up I had difficulty breathing, talking and walking. I called on nurse. She asked questions and told me to call 911. My husband drove me to hospital in because it was faster than getting an ambulance. On the way to hospital swelling increased to left jaw and left ear.  At Hospital I was seen by many nurses, I received 2 Pepcid, a Benadryl shot and a steroid shot. Due to the location of pain they were concerned they were concerned that something was wrong with my heart or I was having a heart attack. They took blood tests and chest xrays and did an EKG. Then they had me wait for a long time then did another EKG because they didn't like the results of first EKG. No changes in EKG's.  They prescribed Pepcid 20 mg BID and Prednisone 2 20 mg tablets once a day. RX for Epi-pen 2 pack. Started with medications on Monday 4/12/21 morning and took for 5 days as prescribed. Also called primary care on 4/12/21 to inform them of situation. Also called hospital on 4/12/21 asking how to get records and get information

I administered the MODERNA vaccine to patient. He directly went to sit in the waiting area. About 1 and 1/2 minutes later we were told by a customer that we had a patient in our waiting area laying on the floor. I immediately went out and saw him and told the staff to call 911. His body started convulsing and I repeated to call the manager and 911. I got down on the floor on his left side. He was face first in the concrete. There was a man sitting beside him with his hand on his back. He didn't look like he was breathing and I wanted to turn him on his back, but he started making sounds and I left him lay like he was. His body started convulsing again. Then store management appeared. The man started to lift his head and I could see that his nose looked cracked open and he was bleeding. He tried to get to a position on his knees and then I could see blood on the floor and coming from his mouth. I told him to continue to lay down and that the ambulance was coming. 2 fireman came over to assess the situation.  Then there was a woman there next to patient. It was his mother. She said that he has a history of fainting after shots. The man that was by patient's side on the floor was his father. EMS got there and started to take care of him. At this point he got to a sitting position against the wall. He did not remember any of what had happened. The EMS wanted to take him by ambulance to the hospital but patient was agitated and did not want to go by ambulance to the hospital. He thought he was fine but we were trying to tell him what had happened to him. He got up and went to the front with the EMS to sign a form. His mother and father wanted him to go to hospital to get checked out because he has never had a seizure before. We have not heard anything back yet.

Patient was scheduled for his first Moderna vaccine on Friday April 23rd at 3:00 pm. Intern administered the vaccine. After receiving the vaccination patient was instructed to wait in the designated waiting area for 15 minutes. After 5-10 minutes, patient walked over to the drop-off window and stated that he was having a hard time breathing and his hands were going numb. Pharmacist on duty, immediately left the pharmacy and walked over to the patient. The patient then fainted in his arms and pharmacist was able to gently bring him to the ground. Patient wanted pharmacist to call and notify his wife which at the time was waiting in her car. His wife arrived immediately. Technician, called 911 and ran EpiPen over to pharmacist and technician prepared a damp cloth and placed it behind patients neck. Pharmacist then administered one dose of adult Epi-pen. Minutes later patient still said he could not breathe and that his symptoms were getting worse. Pharmacist then administered second dose of Epi-pen. Within 3-5 minutes after receiving second Epi-pen dose, the ambulance came. EMT's gave the patient oxygen and placed him on a gurney. EMT's then took patient to ambulance and drove him to hospital. Going through patient's immunization consent form and in talking to patient, there was no indication that the patient has ever had any reactions to any vaccinations in the past.
Dose #2 given too early (at day 21) dose #1 done 4/2/21
Difficulty in breathing, Left upper quadrant pain.ED visit 3/16/2021. Pulmonary emboli diagnosis. Unprovoked.

20 yr old Female patient received first dose Pfizer covid19 vaccine in left arm administered by pharmacy intern at 3:27pm .  supervising pharmacist was (Name) pharmD.   Prior to patient receiving the covid19 vaccine  pharmD reviewed and went over all the DUR and digital patient questionnaire questions.  Mother of patient was present and mentioned that in the patient's past , the patient had fainted after receiving a vaccine.  PharmD told patient that because this occurred in the past, the patient will have to wait 30 minutes after vaccine administration for observation.    Patient was sitting in post-vaccination area, and about 3 minutes later patient's father notified staff , that patient felt dizzy and  looked pale and had blurry vision and patient was sweating.  PharmD  asked the patient if she had any difficulty breathing and if she felt itchy or had any rash as a result of the vaccine reaction.    We immediately called the pharmacy and notified (Name) of the situation.  The patient refused us to contact 911 and refused 911 care.  The pharmacy manager immediately arrived to the Clinic fitting room area.  Upon arrival,  the pharmacy manager provided alcohol swabs to patient to inhale because at that moment we did not have ammonia inhalants. PharmD  quickly made his way to the pharmacy to obtain the ammonia inhalants , which is a respiratory stimulant.  The pharmD returned to the Covid19 clinic with ammonia inhalants, which were never used, because we did not see the need.  Patient remained conscious the entire incident.    We decided not to  use epinephrine.   The pharmD measured the patient's blood pressure at 3:38pm .  bp reading was 109/65.  Pharmacy manager took pt temperature at 3:45pm, reading was 97F.  Pharmacy manager retook blood pressure at 4pm.  bp reading was 93/63, pulse of  72.   The pharmacy manager advised the patient to seek medical attention if patient continues to get worse.  bp was lower the second reading.  The pharmacy manager asked  patient a second time at 4pm if patient wanted us to call 911 again, and again patient refused us to contact 911.

Pneumococcal serotype-specific IgG levels were undetectable to 20 of 23 serotypes tested at baseline, and only 4 were considered protective post-vaccination;   This literature marketed report has been received from authors of a published article, titled as above, regarding a 31 years old female patient.  The patient presented with asthma, atopic dermatitis, allergic rhinitis, and a history of episodic fatigue and sinusitis for several years. Episodic fatigue occurred every 2-3 weeks and was described as not feeling rested even after 12 h of sleep. Chronic sinusitis was treated with 4-5 prolonged antibiotic courses per year. Nasal cultures grew methicillinsensitive and methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus and Haemophilus irifluenzae. Three separate sinus surgeries over the prior few years moderately reduced her sinus symptoms. Other relevant history was significant for recurrent urinary tract infections with E. coli and Klebsiella, recurrent otitis media as a child, and a diagnosis of transient hypogammaglobulinemia of infancy that resolved at 4 years of age.  Review of systems revealed intermittent axillary lymphadenopathy, longstanding eczema that responded to topical tacrolimus, multiple environmental allergies, and recently diagnosed asthma that improved with inhaled budesonide (+) formoterol. As a teenager, she received allergen immunotherapy (AIT) for a few years but stopped due to frequent adverse reactions. Family history revealed that her mother received AIT for seasonal allergies, and her father died from infection associated with chemotherapy for non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. Physical exam at the initial evaluation was only remarkable for nasal turbinate hypertrophy.  Laboratory evaluation demonstrated normal immunoglobulin G (IgG) 886 mg/dL, immunoglobulin M (IgM) 139 mg/dL, immunoglobulin A (IgA) 156 mg/dL, elevated immunoglobulin E (IgE) 373 kU/L, normal T and natural killer (NK) cell enumeration, slightly decreased total B cells (180 cells/microliter, 5.6% of lymphocytes), and normal B cell subsets (CD19+CD27-IgM+ 67%, CD19+ CD27+IgM+17%, CD19+IgM-CD27+ 13%). Tetanus antibody titer was protective (0.27 IU/mL), but haemophilus influenzae type B (Hib) antibody titer was undetectable at less than 0.15 IU/mL and not protective after vaccination (0.53 IU/mL). Pneumococcal serotype-specific lgG levels were undetectable to 20 of 23 serotypes tested at baseline, and only 4 were considered protective post-vaccination with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) (antibody test negative). QuantiFERON gold assays consistently showed interferon (IFN)-gamma release more than 10.00 IU/mL in response to "PHA" (positive control), demonstrating T cell responsiveness to this mitogen. Due to poor antibody response and continued sinus infections, she was started on IgG replacement for the diagnosis of specific antibody deficiency. Her fatigue and sinus symptoms improved moderately, but she continued to require antibiotics. Sinus computed tomography (CT) scans continued to demonstrate significant disease. An in-house focused exome panel showed only a novel heterozygous caspase recruitment domain family member 11 (CARD11) variant (c.215G more than T, p.R72L). Specific antibody deficiency as observed in the patient was commonly seen in CARD11-associated atopy with dominant interference of nuclear factor kappa-light-chain-enhancer of activated B cells (NF-kappaB) signaling (CADINS). The outcome of the event antibody test negative was unknown.  The causality between the event and pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) was assessed as related.  A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.
